1
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:11,880
Hello, everyone, and welcome
to lecture 8 of CME 295.

2
00:00:11,880 --> 00:00:16,239
So today's topic will
be LLM evaluation.

3
00:00:16,239 --> 00:00:18,200
And I think this
class is probably

4
00:00:18,200 --> 00:00:21,460
one of the most important
classes of this quarter

5
00:00:21,460 --> 00:00:25,120
because the idea
is if we don't how

6
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:27,760
to measure the
performance of our LLM,

7
00:00:27,760 --> 00:00:30,200
we don't really know
what to improve.

8
00:00:30,200 --> 00:00:32,920
And so this class
will focus on how

9
00:00:32,920 --> 00:00:36,200
we can quantify how
the LLM performs

10
00:00:36,200 --> 00:00:39,280
in a bunch of different cases.

11
00:00:39,280 --> 00:00:41,720
So with that said,
we are going to start

12
00:00:41,720 --> 00:00:46,720
the class as usual by recapping
what we saw last week.

13
00:00:46,720 --> 00:00:49,920
So if you remember,
last week, we

14
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:55,080
saw how our LLM could
interact with systems that

15
00:00:55,080 --> 00:00:58,160
are outside of the LLM itself.

16
00:00:58,160 --> 00:01:01,480
So we saw one core
technique that

17
00:01:01,480 --> 00:01:07,320
is called RAG that allows
our LLM to fetch information

18
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:10,440
from external knowledge bases.

19
00:01:10,440 --> 00:01:17,320
And so here RAG stands for
Retrieval-Augmented Generation.

20
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:21,700
And we saw how we could
improve the retrieval system.

21
00:01:21,700 --> 00:01:25,580
So we saw that it was
composed of two main steps.

22
00:01:25,580 --> 00:01:28,360
So one was candidate
retrieval, which

23
00:01:28,360 --> 00:01:34,840
is typically something that is
done with a bi-encoder setup.

24
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:38,280
So Sentence-BERT
was a good example

25
00:01:38,280 --> 00:01:42,760
of how people would
design such a model.

26
00:01:42,760 --> 00:01:46,080
And so this first step
is typically there

27
00:01:46,080 --> 00:01:50,560
to filter down the potential
relevant candidates for a given

28
00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:52,640
incoming query.

29
00:01:52,640 --> 00:01:54,840
And then we saw that there
was a second step, which

30
00:01:54,840 --> 00:02:02,350
was reranking, and that one was
a bit more involved and involved

31
00:02:02,350 --> 00:02:06,070
cross-encoders, which
were more sophisticated.

32
00:02:06,070 --> 00:02:10,389
And we also saw some ways to
quantify how well our retrieval

33
00:02:10,389 --> 00:02:12,990
system performed.

34
00:02:12,990 --> 00:02:14,910
And then we also
saw something that

35
00:02:14,910 --> 00:02:17,750
was called tool
calling, which is

36
00:02:17,750 --> 00:02:21,550
the ability for a
model to which tool

37
00:02:21,550 --> 00:02:25,110
to call with which argument.

38
00:02:25,110 --> 00:02:28,350
So if you remember,
if we give our LLM

39
00:02:28,350 --> 00:02:32,550
the knowledge of the tools
that are available to it,

40
00:02:32,550 --> 00:02:35,990
it can figure out
which arguments

41
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:39,550
it needs to input to the
function as a function

42
00:02:39,550 --> 00:02:44,630
of the input query, and then
run that function and then

43
00:02:44,630 --> 00:02:48,380
output the result in natural
language to the user.

44
00:02:51,310 --> 00:02:57,030
And then we also saw how agentic
workflows were composed of.

45
00:02:57,030 --> 00:02:59,790
So spoiler alert,
it's something that

46
00:02:59,790 --> 00:03:03,950
is a combination of the
two previous methods, so

47
00:03:03,950 --> 00:03:06,630
RAG and tool calling.

48
00:03:06,630 --> 00:03:10,230
And in particular,
given an input,

49
00:03:10,230 --> 00:03:14,950
we're allowing our model
to make multiple calls

50
00:03:14,950 --> 00:03:18,430
to call different tools
to fetch relevant data

51
00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:21,990
from other knowledge bases.

52
00:03:21,990 --> 00:03:26,630
And we saw one example
that was successful

53
00:03:26,630 --> 00:03:28,270
from the current
applications, which

54
00:03:28,270 --> 00:03:33,950
was AI-assisted coding, which
relies on this principle.

55
00:03:33,950 --> 00:03:37,450
And React is typically the
framework that people would use.

56
00:03:37,450 --> 00:03:42,950
So reason plus act, which is
decomposing this into observe,

57
00:03:42,950 --> 00:03:47,870
plan, and act steps.

58
00:03:47,870 --> 00:03:48,690
Cool.

59
00:03:48,690 --> 00:03:51,550
So this is what
we saw last time,

60
00:03:51,550 --> 00:03:55,890
and we also so started
from this slide last time.

61
00:03:55,890 --> 00:04:01,820
If you remember, our LLM has
strengths but also weaknesses

62
00:04:01,820 --> 00:04:04,140
that we're trying to mitigate.

63
00:04:04,140 --> 00:04:09,340
So in particular, the
focus of lectures 6 and 7

64
00:04:09,340 --> 00:04:15,880
were on methods to improve
reasoning of the model and ways

65
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:19,980
for the model to fetch
knowledge from other systems,

66
00:04:19,980 --> 00:04:23,900
as well as performing actions.

67
00:04:23,900 --> 00:04:28,300
And today, we're going to
focus on the evaluation part,

68
00:04:28,300 --> 00:04:32,860
in particular, given a response
that the model is giving,

69
00:04:32,860 --> 00:04:37,030
how can we quantify how well
the LLM is giving its response?

70
00:04:40,900 --> 00:04:42,280
Cool.

71
00:04:42,280 --> 00:04:47,380
So first of all, I would like
to define the term "evaluation"

72
00:04:47,380 --> 00:04:51,380
and the meaning that we
will use for this lecture.

73
00:04:51,380 --> 00:04:55,140
So when we say, I want
to evaluate my LLM,

74
00:04:55,140 --> 00:04:58,580
it can actually take a
lot of different meanings.

75
00:04:58,580 --> 00:05:01,000
So when you say, let's
evaluate the LLM,

76
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:05,880
it can mean let's evaluate
the performance, the output.

77
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:09,360
Let's evaluate this based
on coherence, factuality.

78
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:13,260
Let's evaluate it based
on latency, so more

79
00:05:13,260 --> 00:05:16,820
system-related
metrics or pricing

80
00:05:16,820 --> 00:05:20,700
or how often it is up and so on.

81
00:05:20,700 --> 00:05:22,900
So just to make sure
we're on the same page,

82
00:05:22,900 --> 00:05:28,940
this lecture will mostly focus
on the output quality part.

83
00:05:28,940 --> 00:05:33,020
And in particular, we'll
focus on quantifying how

84
00:05:33,020 --> 00:05:37,780
good the actual response is.

85
00:05:37,780 --> 00:05:41,220
And here you will note that
this is a challenging problem

86
00:05:41,220 --> 00:05:46,140
because as we saw
previously, our LLM is

87
00:05:46,140 --> 00:05:53,540
a text-to-text model that can
output basically anything.

88
00:05:53,540 --> 00:05:56,720
So it can be natural
language, it can be code,

89
00:05:56,720 --> 00:06:01,700
it can be math reasoning,
and so on and so forth.

90
00:06:01,700 --> 00:06:05,660
So it's very hard to come
up with universal metrics

91
00:06:05,660 --> 00:06:06,560
to evaluate that.

92
00:06:06,560 --> 00:06:08,710
So we will see how people
do this in practice.

93
00:06:12,140 --> 00:06:12,760
Cool.

94
00:06:12,760 --> 00:06:20,460
So given the fact that our LLM
generates free-form output,

95
00:06:20,460 --> 00:06:24,140
one could imagine that
the ideal scenario for us

96
00:06:24,140 --> 00:06:30,540
to evaluate the LLM output
would be to every time

97
00:06:30,540 --> 00:06:34,740
ask a human to
rate the response.

98
00:06:34,740 --> 00:06:36,700
So here the ideal
scenario would be,

99
00:06:36,700 --> 00:06:39,300
OK, I give a prompt to my LLM.

100
00:06:39,300 --> 00:06:40,900
It gives a response.

101
00:06:40,900 --> 00:06:46,620
I ask a human to rate it,
and I start again and again.

102
00:06:46,620 --> 00:06:49,390
And what I do is at
the end of the day,

103
00:06:49,390 --> 00:06:51,890
I just collect all
these human responses,

104
00:06:51,890 --> 00:06:56,490
and I try to quantify the
overall performance of my model.

105
00:06:56,490 --> 00:06:59,450
Well, as you can
imagine, the main problem

106
00:06:59,450 --> 00:07:06,210
is that such a system would
be very cost-intensive.

107
00:07:06,210 --> 00:07:09,730
But let's look at
this into more detail.

108
00:07:09,730 --> 00:07:17,530
So if you remember, the LLM
outputs are really free-form.

109
00:07:17,530 --> 00:07:23,650
And there may be cases that even
human judgments may be something

110
00:07:23,650 --> 00:07:27,250
that is fuzzy because maybe
the rating task in itself

111
00:07:27,250 --> 00:07:29,170
is subjective.

112
00:07:29,170 --> 00:07:32,890
So let's take the
following example.

113
00:07:32,890 --> 00:07:38,010
Let's suppose I ask my LLM what
birthday gift should I get.

114
00:07:38,010 --> 00:07:41,490
And let's suppose the LLM
responds with a teddy bear is

115
00:07:41,490 --> 00:07:43,870
almost always a sweet gift.

116
00:07:43,870 --> 00:07:46,210
Just pick one that
feels right for you.

117
00:07:46,210 --> 00:07:47,930
So let's suppose
I want to evaluate

118
00:07:47,930 --> 00:07:52,690
this response with respect
to the usefulness dimension.

119
00:07:52,690 --> 00:07:56,470
I may have one human
reader that says, yeah,

120
00:07:56,470 --> 00:08:01,270
it's pretty useful because teddy
bear is pretty indicative of,

121
00:08:01,270 --> 00:08:05,370
I guess, what the user
should get as a gift.

122
00:08:05,370 --> 00:08:08,650
But then another reader
may say, no, actually,

123
00:08:08,650 --> 00:08:12,370
it's not useful because maybe
the response didn't specify

124
00:08:12,370 --> 00:08:14,410
exactly which teddy bear.

125
00:08:14,410 --> 00:08:17,030
Should I have a bear?

126
00:08:17,030 --> 00:08:19,030
Should I have an
elephant, a giraffe?

127
00:08:19,030 --> 00:08:22,810
Which stuffed
animal should I get?

128
00:08:22,810 --> 00:08:31,810
So there is this notion of
inter-rater agreement, where

129
00:08:31,810 --> 00:08:37,370
we're basically concerned
with making sure that everyone

130
00:08:37,370 --> 00:08:43,530
is aligned on how to rate those
responses because sometimes

131
00:08:43,530 --> 00:08:47,090
like in this
illustrative example,

132
00:08:47,090 --> 00:08:50,570
it's maybe a little
bit subjective.

133
00:08:50,570 --> 00:08:52,890
So responses may vary.

134
00:08:52,890 --> 00:08:56,610
So what people want
to do is to make sure

135
00:08:56,610 --> 00:09:01,410
that the guidelines are clear
enough for everyone to rate

136
00:09:01,410 --> 00:09:04,850
these responses in
a consistent manner.

137
00:09:04,850 --> 00:09:12,170
So people come up with
agreement types of metrics.

138
00:09:12,170 --> 00:09:18,210
So a very natural metric that
you may think of is the quote,

139
00:09:18,210 --> 00:09:21,130
unquote, "agreement rate."

140
00:09:21,130 --> 00:09:24,130
So for instance, you
have these two raters.

141
00:09:24,130 --> 00:09:29,250
So what you do is
you just measure

142
00:09:29,250 --> 00:09:31,210
the proportion of
the time that the two

143
00:09:31,210 --> 00:09:34,730
raters give the same response.

144
00:09:34,730 --> 00:09:36,990
And let's suppose the
response here is binary,

145
00:09:36,990 --> 00:09:41,880
so let's say, yes,
good or not good.

146
00:09:41,880 --> 00:09:47,400
Well, do you see a problem
with such a metric?

147
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:48,510
Is this a good metric?

148
00:09:54,600 --> 00:09:59,040
I guess another way to
ask this question is,

149
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:02,920
if I give you a given
number of agreement rates,

150
00:10:02,920 --> 00:10:09,280
can you tell me if it's a good
number or if it's a bad number?

151
00:10:09,280 --> 00:10:15,880
Well, let's take the example
of, let's say, two raters,

152
00:10:15,880 --> 00:10:21,910
let's say, Alice
and let's say, Bob.

153
00:10:24,480 --> 00:10:28,920
And let's suppose we have two
different types of ratings

154
00:10:28,920 --> 00:10:30,720
that these raters can give.

155
00:10:30,720 --> 00:10:36,040
So either, let's say, yes, it's
good, so 1, the output is good,

156
00:10:36,040 --> 00:10:37,580
or the output is not good.

157
00:10:40,320 --> 00:10:46,080
So if we assume that
the first rater gives,

158
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:52,880
let's say, random responses
with some probability P of A

159
00:10:52,880 --> 00:10:58,600
for being good and 1 minus
P of A for being not good.

160
00:10:58,600 --> 00:11:04,040
And then, let's say, Bob, who
should have eyes and a smile,

161
00:11:04,040 --> 00:11:08,560
has a P of B for being
good and 1 minus P

162
00:11:08,560 --> 00:11:09,790
of B for being not good.

163
00:11:13,360 --> 00:11:18,160
Then let's compute the
agreement rate for this case.

164
00:11:18,160 --> 00:11:26,240
So the agreement rate is
basically the probability

165
00:11:26,240 --> 00:11:35,120
that rater A and rater B agree.

166
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:44,270
And so here A and B agree
if A and B both vote 1

167
00:11:44,270 --> 00:11:47,266
or when A and B both vote 0.

168
00:11:50,630 --> 00:11:54,870
But if they give their response
in an independent and random

169
00:11:54,870 --> 00:12:01,923
way, well, if you use this
probability concepts that you

170
00:12:01,923 --> 00:12:07,750
know, then we will have
probability of A and B

171
00:12:07,750 --> 00:12:11,790
responding to 1, which is
probability of A responding to 1

172
00:12:11,790 --> 00:12:16,150
times probability of B
responding to 1, and same for 0.

173
00:12:16,150 --> 00:12:18,830
So we will have
something like this.

174
00:12:18,830 --> 00:12:26,470
So P of A, P of B
plus 1 minus P of A,

175
00:12:26,470 --> 00:12:37,310
1 minus P of B. So this
one is A and B say 1

176
00:12:37,310 --> 00:12:43,380
And here A and B say 0.

177
00:12:49,725 --> 00:12:54,070
So let's see what the agreement
rate would be in that case.

178
00:12:54,070 --> 00:13:01,950
So if we assume that suppose
that-- let's suppose,

179
00:13:01,950 --> 00:13:08,430
P of A is equal to P of B, which
is equal to, let's say, 0.5,

180
00:13:08,430 --> 00:13:11,270
then the agreement
rate would be--

181
00:13:11,270 --> 00:13:18,750
so agreement rate would be--

182
00:13:18,750 --> 00:13:20,850
so I'm just replacing
the numbers here,

183
00:13:20,850 --> 00:13:26,690
so 0.5 squared plus 0.5 squared.

184
00:13:26,690 --> 00:13:30,130
So it's 0.25 plus 0.25,
which is equal to 0.5.

185
00:13:30,130 --> 00:13:36,390
So what that means is if
we're just letting our raters

186
00:13:36,390 --> 00:13:40,550
rate these things in a random
way with some probability

187
00:13:40,550 --> 00:13:45,150
P of A, P of B, we would already
have an agreement rate of 50%,

188
00:13:45,150 --> 00:13:48,310
just by pure random chance.

189
00:13:48,310 --> 00:13:51,590
And so one thing
that I want to say

190
00:13:51,590 --> 00:13:56,030
is, that this agreement
rates, by pure chance,

191
00:13:56,030 --> 00:14:01,350
is a function of the probability
that each of these raters

192
00:14:01,350 --> 00:14:03,590
give these ratings.

193
00:14:03,590 --> 00:14:07,070
And so if this probability
is actually higher,

194
00:14:07,070 --> 00:14:12,030
the agreement rates by
pure chance is also higher.

195
00:14:12,030 --> 00:14:12,890
So what that means?

196
00:14:12,890 --> 00:14:14,950
So what do I want to say?

197
00:14:14,950 --> 00:14:18,750
I want to say that if we just
take the agreement rates,

198
00:14:18,750 --> 00:14:22,070
then it's very hard
to put it into context

199
00:14:22,070 --> 00:14:26,470
in terms of what you would have
gotten if things would have

200
00:14:26,470 --> 00:14:28,480
happened just by pure chance.

201
00:14:31,070 --> 00:14:37,100
So for this reason,
people have come up

202
00:14:37,100 --> 00:14:44,140
with a series of metrics that
try to make it more relative

203
00:14:44,140 --> 00:14:50,060
to this baseline, which is, what
would happen if our raters would

204
00:14:50,060 --> 00:14:53,260
choose things randomly?

205
00:14:53,260 --> 00:14:56,680
And so you have these
metrics-- like for instance,

206
00:14:56,680 --> 00:14:59,660
this one is the
Cohen's kappa metric,

207
00:14:59,660 --> 00:15:07,500
which computes a quantity that
is a function of this agreement

208
00:15:07,500 --> 00:15:13,060
rate by chance, and
take the observed one,

209
00:15:13,060 --> 00:15:22,100
such that if our observed
agreement rate is greater than

210
00:15:22,100 --> 00:15:26,860
the "by chance" agreement
rate, then our coefficient is

211
00:15:26,860 --> 00:15:27,360
positive.

212
00:15:27,360 --> 00:15:29,260
So when it's
positive, at least you

213
00:15:29,260 --> 00:15:32,900
know it's going in
the right direction.

214
00:15:32,900 --> 00:15:40,140
So here, if the observed
agreement rate is equal to 1,

215
00:15:40,140 --> 00:15:44,260
then kappa is equal to 1.

216
00:15:44,260 --> 00:15:50,820
But if our observed agreement
rate is below the "by pure

217
00:15:50,820 --> 00:15:54,980
random chance" agreement rate
that we saw on the blackboard,

218
00:15:54,980 --> 00:15:59,060
then our coefficient
would be negative.

219
00:15:59,060 --> 00:16:01,900
So long story short,
there is a bunch

220
00:16:01,900 --> 00:16:06,940
of metrics that try to
quantify inter-rater agreement

221
00:16:06,940 --> 00:16:10,620
rates using these
kinds of formulas

222
00:16:10,620 --> 00:16:15,820
to be able to make these
quantities relative to what

223
00:16:15,820 --> 00:16:20,700
would happen if things
were done in a random way.

224
00:16:20,700 --> 00:16:24,520
And so that's why you may see
a bunch of metrics out there.

225
00:16:24,520 --> 00:16:28,740
So here is Cohen's kappa
that people use for cases

226
00:16:28,740 --> 00:16:30,300
where there are two
raters, but then

227
00:16:30,300 --> 00:16:33,700
you have extensions,
such as Fleiss's kappa

228
00:16:33,700 --> 00:16:37,180
and Krippendorff's alpha
that you may see out there.

229
00:16:37,180 --> 00:16:41,180
So they all rely on
this idea that we

230
00:16:41,180 --> 00:16:46,900
should have some baseline,
which is our raters just

231
00:16:46,900 --> 00:16:49,460
randomly picking
answers, and try

232
00:16:49,460 --> 00:16:54,740
to see how much better our
actual agreement is compared

233
00:16:54,740 --> 00:16:56,930
to this.

234
00:16:56,930 --> 00:16:57,930
So does that make sense?

235
00:17:01,140 --> 00:17:06,060
So I guess what I want to say
is that the first limitation

236
00:17:06,060 --> 00:17:11,079
of asking humans to
rate our LLM outputs,

237
00:17:11,079 --> 00:17:15,579
which was sometimes the
task being subjective,

238
00:17:15,579 --> 00:17:17,940
can be something
that we can quantify

239
00:17:17,940 --> 00:17:22,420
with this inter-rater
agreement metrics.

240
00:17:22,420 --> 00:17:24,700
So what people
would typically do

241
00:17:24,700 --> 00:17:30,570
is they keep track of how
good that agreement is.

242
00:17:30,570 --> 00:17:33,170
And if, let's say, we
have a quantity that's not

243
00:17:33,170 --> 00:17:38,610
satisfactory, people would
just hold some quote, unquote,

244
00:17:38,610 --> 00:17:43,130
"agreement sessions" between the
raters to just align on how they

245
00:17:43,130 --> 00:17:50,010
should rate the answers so that
it can be seen as just a health

246
00:17:50,010 --> 00:17:54,490
metric to track how
consistent your ratings are.

247
00:17:54,490 --> 00:18:00,730
And this is typically something
that people use in practice.

248
00:18:00,730 --> 00:18:08,090
So up until now, we've seen one
limitation of human ratings.

249
00:18:08,090 --> 00:18:11,810
Well, second limitation, I
think I also said it previously.

250
00:18:11,810 --> 00:18:13,050
It's really slow.

251
00:18:13,050 --> 00:18:16,330
If you ask someone to rate
a thousand LLM outputs,

252
00:18:16,330 --> 00:18:18,970
well, it will take them a while.

253
00:18:18,970 --> 00:18:22,570
And it's, of course, expensive.

254
00:18:22,570 --> 00:18:29,210
So all of that to say that
our ideal scenario of asking

255
00:18:29,210 --> 00:18:32,810
a human to rate every
LLM output is not

256
00:18:32,810 --> 00:18:35,450
something that is practical.

257
00:18:35,450 --> 00:18:42,990
But we can leverage
human ratings in some way

258
00:18:42,990 --> 00:18:46,610
because we've seen that even
if the task is subjective,

259
00:18:46,610 --> 00:18:51,610
we can have a way
to align our raters.

260
00:18:51,610 --> 00:18:56,010
So now let's move on to
another way to go about doing

261
00:18:56,010 --> 00:19:01,570
this, which is by using
some rule-based metrics.

262
00:19:01,570 --> 00:19:04,530
So here I'm just going
to revise the setting

263
00:19:04,530 --> 00:19:06,810
that I mentioned before.

264
00:19:06,810 --> 00:19:11,930
And instead of asking our
humans to write every LLM

265
00:19:11,930 --> 00:19:15,570
output, this time,
I'm just going

266
00:19:15,570 --> 00:19:22,720
to ask them to write the
references or the ideal outputs

267
00:19:22,720 --> 00:19:28,120
for a given set of prompts,
just fix that for good,

268
00:19:28,120 --> 00:19:34,360
and then use some kind of metric
that would compare the LLM

269
00:19:34,360 --> 00:19:37,340
outputs with those references.

270
00:19:39,960 --> 00:19:43,560
So here the main difference
is, let's suppose I have

271
00:19:43,560 --> 00:19:46,880
a given set of prompts fixed.

272
00:19:46,880 --> 00:19:50,360
Well, I can make
iterations in my model

273
00:19:50,360 --> 00:19:54,440
and always compare
the outputs of my LLM

274
00:19:54,440 --> 00:19:59,560
with this fixed reference,
instead of always asking humans

275
00:19:59,560 --> 00:20:01,640
to rate that again and again.

276
00:20:01,640 --> 00:20:05,120
So it's already an improvement.

277
00:20:05,120 --> 00:20:08,160
And we will see
a little bit what

278
00:20:08,160 --> 00:20:10,520
are the kinds of
rule-based metrics

279
00:20:10,520 --> 00:20:14,040
that you will see out there.

280
00:20:14,040 --> 00:20:19,720
So ideally, these
metrics should reflect

281
00:20:19,720 --> 00:20:24,540
the performance of the LLM
output in an optimal way.

282
00:20:24,540 --> 00:20:26,760
And what I mean
by an optimal way,

283
00:20:26,760 --> 00:20:31,040
it is to make it be a
little bit flexible,

284
00:20:31,040 --> 00:20:35,800
given the fact that natural
language is not always something

285
00:20:35,800 --> 00:20:39,480
that you can say
in one given way.

286
00:20:39,480 --> 00:20:43,000
So for instance, when I provide
a response to a given prompt,

287
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:44,680
there can be very
well a case where

288
00:20:44,680 --> 00:20:48,440
I can formulate the response
slightly differently,

289
00:20:48,440 --> 00:20:52,480
but it will still
be just as good.

290
00:20:52,480 --> 00:20:55,360
So the idea behind
this matrix is

291
00:20:55,360 --> 00:20:58,670
to make this comparison
a little bit flexible.

292
00:21:01,920 --> 00:21:03,920
So let's start
with one common one

293
00:21:03,920 --> 00:21:06,840
that people use in
the translation case.

294
00:21:06,840 --> 00:21:10,520
So this metric is
called METEOR, and it

295
00:21:10,520 --> 00:21:13,080
stands for metric for
evaluation of translation

296
00:21:13,080 --> 00:21:15,760
with explicit ordering.

297
00:21:15,760 --> 00:21:23,520
So the idea here is to compare
reference and predicted,

298
00:21:23,520 --> 00:21:26,200
and we'll see how
it's being done,

299
00:21:26,200 --> 00:21:33,440
and also penalize cases
when words are not

300
00:21:33,440 --> 00:21:37,840
in the same order, which is
explaining why the metric is

301
00:21:37,840 --> 00:21:41,040
called with explicit ordering.

302
00:21:41,040 --> 00:21:42,620
So the formula is as follows.

303
00:21:42,620 --> 00:21:47,710
So it is some F score
times 1 minus some penalty.

304
00:21:50,280 --> 00:21:53,800
So the F score here is--

305
00:21:53,800 --> 00:21:55,960
you may be familiar
with F1 score.

306
00:21:55,960 --> 00:21:59,280
So it's like the harmonic
mean with equal weights.

307
00:21:59,280 --> 00:22:02,640
So this one is with
the variable weights.

308
00:22:02,640 --> 00:22:07,360
So it is a function of
precision and recall,

309
00:22:07,360 --> 00:22:13,240
where precision is the
proportion of the unigrams that

310
00:22:13,240 --> 00:22:18,150
are in your predicted
sequence that are

311
00:22:18,150 --> 00:22:20,390
matching with the reference.

312
00:22:20,390 --> 00:22:23,430
And the recall is the
proportion of the unigrams

313
00:22:23,430 --> 00:22:27,430
in the reference
that are matching

314
00:22:27,430 --> 00:22:29,710
with what is in the predicted.

315
00:22:29,710 --> 00:22:34,950
So it's basically matching the
usual precision recall metrics

316
00:22:34,950 --> 00:22:36,710
that you know.

317
00:22:36,710 --> 00:22:40,130
And then we have
another quantity here,

318
00:22:40,130 --> 00:22:41,010
which is the penalty.

319
00:22:41,010 --> 00:22:43,670
And I mentioned the
penalty here tries

320
00:22:43,670 --> 00:22:47,570
to incentivize good ordering.

321
00:22:47,570 --> 00:22:51,510
So if it's ordered the
same in the reference

322
00:22:51,510 --> 00:22:54,470
and in the prediction,
then it's good.

323
00:22:54,470 --> 00:22:56,950
Otherwise, it's bad.

324
00:22:56,950 --> 00:22:59,210
And so here there's a
bunch of quantities.

325
00:22:59,210 --> 00:23:04,190
So gamma and beta are
hyperparameters that people

326
00:23:04,190 --> 00:23:06,350
arbitrarily choose.

327
00:23:06,350 --> 00:23:13,430
And it's a function of C, the
number of contiguous chunks

328
00:23:13,430 --> 00:23:20,160
that are matched over the
number of matched unigrams.

329
00:23:23,150 --> 00:23:29,170
So ideally, you would want C
that would be as low as possible

330
00:23:29,170 --> 00:23:34,310
because if you have a low
number of contiguous matches,

331
00:23:34,310 --> 00:23:39,030
it means that your contiguous
sequences are long,

332
00:23:39,030 --> 00:23:42,990
which means that the
ordering is the same.

333
00:23:42,990 --> 00:23:50,150
So you want C to be low and then
matched unigrams to be high.

334
00:23:50,150 --> 00:23:55,242
So you want that penalty
term to be low for a good--

335
00:23:55,242 --> 00:23:57,830
I guess, for a prediction
that has the same ordering

336
00:23:57,830 --> 00:24:01,150
as the reference.

337
00:24:01,150 --> 00:24:10,350
So I guess higher METEOR score
means better translation,

338
00:24:10,350 --> 00:24:13,980
according to this
way of doing things.

339
00:24:13,980 --> 00:24:17,220
So I guess when you
look at this formula--

340
00:24:17,220 --> 00:24:21,840
first of all, it
looks very arbitrary.

341
00:24:21,840 --> 00:24:25,560
I have alpha as a
hyperparameter, gamma, beta.

342
00:24:25,560 --> 00:24:29,540
So it's kind a recipe, I feel.

343
00:24:29,540 --> 00:24:31,580
So that's one.

344
00:24:31,580 --> 00:24:34,780
And the second thing
is that it does not

345
00:24:34,780 --> 00:24:39,580
allow for stylistic variations
because here we're measuring

346
00:24:39,580 --> 00:24:42,980
the number of matched unigrams.

347
00:24:42,980 --> 00:24:47,900
Although the metric
expands the range

348
00:24:47,900 --> 00:24:52,180
of what it's called matched
unigrams by taking into account

349
00:24:52,180 --> 00:24:56,340
things like words that are
synonyms of one another

350
00:24:56,340 --> 00:25:00,640
and things that are of
the same roots, but still,

351
00:25:00,640 --> 00:25:06,780
it is not extremely
satisfactory in that sense.

352
00:25:06,780 --> 00:25:11,020
So METEOR is one such metric.

353
00:25:11,020 --> 00:25:12,980
You have another one
that's being used

354
00:25:12,980 --> 00:25:16,940
or that has been used in
translation tasks, which

355
00:25:16,940 --> 00:25:20,380
is called BLEU,
which you may know.

356
00:25:20,380 --> 00:25:24,300
So BLEU stands for bilingual
evaluation understudy.

357
00:25:24,300 --> 00:25:30,380
And you can think of this as a
precision-focused kind of metric

358
00:25:30,380 --> 00:25:38,500
that looks at the number
of matching n-grams

359
00:25:38,500 --> 00:25:41,820
over the n-grams that are in the
prediction, which is why it's

360
00:25:41,820 --> 00:25:45,260
a precision kind of metric.

361
00:25:45,260 --> 00:25:48,780
And it also has a penalty term.

362
00:25:48,780 --> 00:25:52,340
Here it's called brevity
penalty because given

363
00:25:52,340 --> 00:25:55,380
that it's more of a
precision kind of metric,

364
00:25:55,380 --> 00:25:58,673
if you translate something
that's very short,

365
00:25:58,673 --> 00:26:02,000
you may be able to
gain the metric.

366
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:07,740
So you want to penalize the
translation being too short.

367
00:26:07,740 --> 00:26:10,360
So we're not go going
to a lot of details,

368
00:26:10,360 --> 00:26:12,620
but I just want to just show
you the kinds of metrics

369
00:26:12,620 --> 00:26:13,412
that are out there.

370
00:26:13,412 --> 00:26:17,140
So METEOR is one,
BLEU is another one.

371
00:26:17,140 --> 00:26:19,500
And ROUGE, which
you may have heard,

372
00:26:19,500 --> 00:26:23,860
is also another one, typically
used for summarization tasks.

373
00:26:23,860 --> 00:26:27,820
Again, same idea,
and it has a bunch

374
00:26:27,820 --> 00:26:31,700
of variants that you
may see out there.

375
00:26:31,700 --> 00:26:36,260
But long story short, all
these metrics, they all

376
00:26:36,260 --> 00:26:42,420
compare the output
with a reference.

377
00:26:42,420 --> 00:26:47,740
So as we saw, one key
limitation is that they do not

378
00:26:47,740 --> 00:26:51,340
allow stylistic variation.

379
00:26:51,340 --> 00:26:53,780
So let's take an example.

380
00:26:53,780 --> 00:26:55,940
So let's suppose I
say, a plush teddy bear

381
00:26:55,940 --> 00:26:58,460
can comfort a child
during bedtime.

382
00:26:58,460 --> 00:27:00,900
Well, the exact same
thing, you can say it--

383
00:27:00,900 --> 00:27:03,280
I can say it in a
really different way.

384
00:27:03,280 --> 00:27:06,780
So soft stuffed
bears often help kids

385
00:27:06,780 --> 00:27:10,130
feel safe as they fall
asleep, or many youngsters

386
00:27:10,130 --> 00:27:12,770
rest more easily at night
when they cuddle a gentle toy

387
00:27:12,770 --> 00:27:13,350
companion.

388
00:27:13,350 --> 00:27:17,990
So in all these cases,
the metrics that we saw

389
00:27:17,990 --> 00:27:20,280
would really
perform very poorly.

390
00:27:23,010 --> 00:27:24,670
So that's one key limitation.

391
00:27:24,670 --> 00:27:30,570
So the second key limitation is
correlation is not that great.

392
00:27:30,570 --> 00:27:32,810
I mean, you can imagine
that people have come up

393
00:27:32,810 --> 00:27:37,450
with all these
hyperparameters to make

394
00:27:37,450 --> 00:27:40,570
it be correlated
to human ratings,

395
00:27:40,570 --> 00:27:44,090
but they're not that correlated.

396
00:27:44,090 --> 00:27:48,690
And the bottom line is, it still
requires human ratings to just

397
00:27:48,690 --> 00:27:50,330
get started.

398
00:27:50,330 --> 00:27:54,250
And sometimes you
just can't afford

399
00:27:54,250 --> 00:27:58,610
to have human ratings,
maybe in your project.

400
00:27:58,610 --> 00:28:02,690
So I guess there are still
some key limitations, which

401
00:28:02,690 --> 00:28:04,010
is the reason why--

402
00:28:04,010 --> 00:28:08,770
all of that to say, I want to
motivate the key methods of this

403
00:28:08,770 --> 00:28:13,210
class or of this lecture,
which is called LLM-as-a-Judge.

404
00:28:16,370 --> 00:28:18,930
We spent the first
seven lectures

405
00:28:18,930 --> 00:28:22,770
motivating these large language
models that are pretrained

406
00:28:22,770 --> 00:28:27,450
on huge amounts of data
that are tuned in a way

407
00:28:27,450 --> 00:28:29,730
to match human preference.

408
00:28:29,730 --> 00:28:31,910
So they do contain
human knowledge.

409
00:28:31,910 --> 00:28:38,650
They do contain some indication
of what humans may prefer.

410
00:28:38,650 --> 00:28:45,210
So the idea here is to have
our model response be actually

411
00:28:45,210 --> 00:28:49,770
an input of yet another LLM.

412
00:28:49,770 --> 00:28:53,170
And that LLM is something
that people typically call

413
00:28:53,170 --> 00:28:55,530
LLM-as-a-Judge.

414
00:28:55,530 --> 00:28:59,090
So it was a term that
was introduced in a paper

415
00:28:59,090 --> 00:29:02,330
from two years ago.

416
00:29:02,330 --> 00:29:09,010
So here the idea is to use
an LLM for rating purposes.

417
00:29:09,010 --> 00:29:11,530
And things that you
would see as input

418
00:29:11,530 --> 00:29:14,850
would be the prompt
that was used

419
00:29:14,850 --> 00:29:21,330
to produce the response, the
response, and the criteria

420
00:29:21,330 --> 00:29:26,530
along which you want
to grade your response.

421
00:29:26,530 --> 00:29:32,530
And so here LLM-as-a-Judge would
give you the following outputs.

422
00:29:32,530 --> 00:29:36,690
So the first thing is it
would give you a score.

423
00:29:36,690 --> 00:29:39,990
So here you can think of
it as a binary scale score,

424
00:29:39,990 --> 00:29:45,930
so pass or fail, and
this is very new, also

425
00:29:45,930 --> 00:29:53,050
a rationale because LLMs,
they understand text.

426
00:29:53,050 --> 00:29:56,770
So they can also explain you
why they graded something

427
00:29:56,770 --> 00:29:58,970
with a given score.

428
00:29:58,970 --> 00:30:03,280
And that part is
the key difference

429
00:30:03,280 --> 00:30:05,000
with previous methods.

430
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:09,880
We are able to explain why
the metric or the model

431
00:30:09,880 --> 00:30:12,520
is giving us a given score.

432
00:30:12,520 --> 00:30:15,740
And this is quite good
because in the other,

433
00:30:15,740 --> 00:30:18,000
let's say, rule-based
world where

434
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:21,520
you would have all these
formulas and multiplication

435
00:30:21,520 --> 00:30:23,720
and all these things,
and sometimes you

436
00:30:23,720 --> 00:30:26,560
would come up with a
number that would not

437
00:30:26,560 --> 00:30:30,280
be very self-explanatory.

438
00:30:30,280 --> 00:30:34,180
And this is luckily something
that LLM-as-a-Judge addresses.

439
00:30:37,120 --> 00:30:43,080
So to recap, what we want
is to use an LLM as a way

440
00:30:43,080 --> 00:30:46,120
to grade the response.

441
00:30:46,120 --> 00:30:51,240
So here you would have typically
the following kind of prompts.

442
00:30:51,240 --> 00:30:54,320
So you would state,
OK, I want to evaluate

443
00:30:54,320 --> 00:30:58,240
my response with respect
to a given criteria.

444
00:30:58,240 --> 00:31:00,360
And then you give
the prompt that you

445
00:31:00,360 --> 00:31:06,840
used to generate that response
along with the model response.

446
00:31:06,840 --> 00:31:11,240
And then you would ask
the judge to return

447
00:31:11,240 --> 00:31:15,490
two things, the rationale
and then the score.

448
00:31:18,040 --> 00:31:20,920
So one little trick
I want to point out

449
00:31:20,920 --> 00:31:26,160
is people typically ask
the model to first output

450
00:31:26,160 --> 00:31:30,240
the rationale and
then the score.

451
00:31:30,240 --> 00:31:34,080
And the reason why we
typically do that is it's

452
00:31:34,080 --> 00:31:36,960
something that
empirically improves

453
00:31:36,960 --> 00:31:40,040
the quality of the results.

454
00:31:40,040 --> 00:31:42,400
But then given what
we saw, I think in,

455
00:31:42,400 --> 00:31:46,000
lecture 6, if you remember
the reasoning class,

456
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:49,720
we saw that these
reasoning models that

457
00:31:49,720 --> 00:31:53,680
are being trendy, especially
in 2025, what they do

458
00:31:53,680 --> 00:31:57,150
is they first output
a chain of thought

459
00:31:57,150 --> 00:31:59,750
before giving the answer.

460
00:31:59,750 --> 00:32:05,710
So you can actually think of
this trick as being on the same

461
00:32:05,710 --> 00:32:10,230
idea of reasoning models,
as in, it allows the model

462
00:32:10,230 --> 00:32:15,270
to externalize, verbalize
its quote, unquote,

463
00:32:15,270 --> 00:32:17,770
"thought process"
before giving the score.

464
00:32:17,770 --> 00:32:22,510
So it gives it a chance to
really figure out what is good

465
00:32:22,510 --> 00:32:25,520
or what is wrong in
the model response.

466
00:32:28,830 --> 00:32:31,710
So far, so good?

467
00:32:31,710 --> 00:32:33,620
Any questions on,
I guess, the setup?

468
00:32:36,270 --> 00:32:37,350
All good.

469
00:32:37,350 --> 00:32:40,670
So now I have a
question for you.

470
00:32:40,670 --> 00:32:45,830
If I give the following
prompts to my LLM-as-a-Judge,

471
00:32:45,830 --> 00:32:51,630
am I guaranteed to have a
rationale and a score that I can

472
00:32:51,630 --> 00:32:53,950
parse?

473
00:32:53,950 --> 00:32:55,250
Am I guaranteed?

474
00:33:01,390 --> 00:33:02,870
No?

475
00:33:02,870 --> 00:33:04,350
Yeah, exactly, no.

476
00:33:04,350 --> 00:33:05,170
The answer is no.

477
00:33:05,170 --> 00:33:10,150
You're not guaranteed to
have a rationale and a score

478
00:33:10,150 --> 00:33:13,150
that you can parse
because this model has

479
00:33:13,150 --> 00:33:16,210
some probabilistic nature to
it with the sampling process.

480
00:33:16,210 --> 00:33:19,190
And it's not something that
you can really control.

481
00:33:19,190 --> 00:33:22,230
So I guess my follow-up
question is, do you

482
00:33:22,230 --> 00:33:26,590
know a technique
that would, I guess,

483
00:33:26,590 --> 00:33:32,590
guarantee you to have
a structured response?

484
00:33:32,590 --> 00:33:38,070
So hint is a technique that
we saw towards the beginning

485
00:33:38,070 --> 00:33:38,680
of the class.

486
00:33:42,970 --> 00:33:44,790
I'll give you a little hint.

487
00:33:44,790 --> 00:33:50,110
So if you remember on
slide 65 of lecture 3,

488
00:33:50,110 --> 00:33:56,550
we saw a technique called
constraints-guided decoding.

489
00:33:56,550 --> 00:34:01,270
So if you remember, the
idea here is to constrain

490
00:34:01,270 --> 00:34:06,270
the decoding thought process
by allowing our model to only

491
00:34:06,270 --> 00:34:11,710
sample from quote,
unquote, "valid" tokens.

492
00:34:11,710 --> 00:34:13,590
And we typically
do that in cases

493
00:34:13,590 --> 00:34:17,230
where we want our output
to have a given format, so

494
00:34:17,230 --> 00:34:19,870
let's suppose, a JSON format.

495
00:34:19,870 --> 00:34:23,350
And we want absolutely
that format.

496
00:34:23,350 --> 00:34:25,510
So what people do is
they use this technique

497
00:34:25,510 --> 00:34:30,750
to guarantee the
form of the response.

498
00:34:30,750 --> 00:34:33,909
And in case you're
using this provider,

499
00:34:33,909 --> 00:34:37,150
like the providers that are out
there, like for instance, OpenAI

500
00:34:37,150 --> 00:34:40,590
or Gemini or Anthropic,
this technique

501
00:34:40,590 --> 00:34:46,510
is known under the
name structured output.

502
00:34:46,510 --> 00:34:51,340
So in your projects, if you
want to constrain the decoding

503
00:34:51,340 --> 00:34:56,900
process in order to output the
response of a given format,

504
00:34:56,900 --> 00:34:59,560
so let's suppose my
format is a response,

505
00:34:59,560 --> 00:35:02,560
and I cannot represent
it by a class,

506
00:35:02,560 --> 00:35:07,580
and there are two attributes,
so rationale and score.

507
00:35:07,580 --> 00:35:10,460
Well, typically,
you can reference

508
00:35:10,460 --> 00:35:14,020
that with the
argument text format

509
00:35:14,020 --> 00:35:18,820
equal to that representation.

510
00:35:18,820 --> 00:35:22,140
So this, I believe, is
something that OpenAI does.

511
00:35:22,140 --> 00:35:25,368
I'm not exactly sure if it's
exactly the argument name

512
00:35:25,368 --> 00:35:27,160
that you would see for
the other providers,

513
00:35:27,160 --> 00:35:31,210
but they're all, I guess,
along the same lines.

514
00:35:33,900 --> 00:35:35,780
Does it sound good?

515
00:35:35,780 --> 00:35:39,460
So the key word here
is structured output.

516
00:35:39,460 --> 00:35:42,300
Whenever you want a
response of a given format,

517
00:35:42,300 --> 00:35:43,840
you would just go for that.

518
00:35:47,180 --> 00:35:47,900
Cool.

519
00:35:47,900 --> 00:35:52,900
So just to recap, our
LLM-as-a-Judge has two main

520
00:35:52,900 --> 00:35:54,380
benefits.

521
00:35:54,380 --> 00:35:59,160
So the first one is that we
do not need a reference text.

522
00:35:59,160 --> 00:36:01,420
We do not need human
ratings to just

523
00:36:01,420 --> 00:36:07,260
get started because our LLM
already has a lot of, I guess,

524
00:36:07,260 --> 00:36:10,180
knowledge that it has acquired
during pretraining and human

525
00:36:10,180 --> 00:36:11,240
preferences and so on.

526
00:36:11,240 --> 00:36:13,940
So you do not need that.

527
00:36:13,940 --> 00:36:16,620
And then the second
thing is you can

528
00:36:16,620 --> 00:36:19,980
interpret the score
with the rationale

529
00:36:19,980 --> 00:36:23,100
that it is being output.

530
00:36:23,100 --> 00:36:26,620
And that is also
quite remarkable.

531
00:36:26,620 --> 00:36:28,820
So just as an example,
here you would say,

532
00:36:28,820 --> 00:36:31,640
evaluate the quality
of this response.

533
00:36:31,640 --> 00:36:33,860
So you would have
some rationale that

534
00:36:33,860 --> 00:36:38,300
would explain what
this response has

535
00:36:38,300 --> 00:36:41,900
or doesn't have that
makes it good or bad

536
00:36:41,900 --> 00:36:42,810
along with the score.

537
00:36:46,540 --> 00:36:47,160
Cool.

538
00:36:47,160 --> 00:36:51,620
And I believe-- now we're
going to see the kinds

539
00:36:51,620 --> 00:36:54,700
of LLM-as-a-Judge that
you can see out there.

540
00:36:54,700 --> 00:36:56,720
Of course, there
are many variations,

541
00:36:56,720 --> 00:36:59,740
but there are generally two
types of LLM-as-a-Judge that you

542
00:36:59,740 --> 00:37:01,460
will see.

543
00:37:01,460 --> 00:37:08,460
So the first one is you have a
single output, a single response

544
00:37:08,460 --> 00:37:10,860
that you want to evaluate.

545
00:37:10,860 --> 00:37:14,300
And here you would ask
LLM-as-a-Judge to say, OK,

546
00:37:14,300 --> 00:37:17,740
is it good, or is it not good?

547
00:37:17,740 --> 00:37:22,780
And the second big kind of
LLM-as-a-Judge that you will see

548
00:37:22,780 --> 00:37:25,360
out there is pairwise
kind of setup.

549
00:37:25,360 --> 00:37:30,900
So you have two responses, and
you say, is response A better,

550
00:37:30,900 --> 00:37:34,540
or is response B better?

551
00:37:34,540 --> 00:37:36,940
And here you would
obtain a response

552
00:37:36,940 --> 00:37:41,340
either that one or this one.

553
00:37:41,340 --> 00:37:44,380
So if you remember, we have
seen in previous lectures

554
00:37:44,380 --> 00:37:48,090
that there are a lot of
situations where we would want

555
00:37:48,090 --> 00:37:51,530
to have preference data, for
instance, in the preference

556
00:37:51,530 --> 00:37:56,250
tuning class that we had,
I believe it was lecture 5.

557
00:37:56,250 --> 00:37:59,050
So these kind of
methods can also

558
00:37:59,050 --> 00:38:04,810
be a good way to synthetically
generate preference ratings

559
00:38:04,810 --> 00:38:07,850
where you have two responses.

560
00:38:07,850 --> 00:38:11,690
And then you ask your LLM to
say, OK, I prefer that one.

561
00:38:11,690 --> 00:38:15,090
And you can use that
one as the label

562
00:38:15,090 --> 00:38:16,460
to train your reward model.

563
00:38:19,170 --> 00:38:22,050
Does it sound good?

564
00:38:22,050 --> 00:38:26,130
Any questions on the
setup or everything

565
00:38:26,130 --> 00:38:27,550
that we've talked about so far?

566
00:38:31,450 --> 00:38:31,950
Cool.

567
00:38:31,950 --> 00:38:35,010
Everyone is on the same page.

568
00:38:35,010 --> 00:38:40,390
So now let's see what can go
wrong with our LLM-as-a-Judge.

569
00:38:40,390 --> 00:38:45,610
So let's think of the
possible kinds of failures

570
00:38:45,610 --> 00:38:48,130
that we can encounter.

571
00:38:48,130 --> 00:38:52,170
So the first one is
called position bias.

572
00:38:52,170 --> 00:38:55,410
And as the name
suggests, it has to do

573
00:38:55,410 --> 00:38:57,970
with the ordering
at which we present

574
00:38:57,970 --> 00:39:00,810
the responses to our model.

575
00:39:00,810 --> 00:39:02,850
So let's say, if
we ask our model,

576
00:39:02,850 --> 00:39:06,570
is response A better
or response B?

577
00:39:06,570 --> 00:39:12,040
Well, there is a chance that the
model responds with response A

578
00:39:12,040 --> 00:39:16,770
just because it was the
first one to be mentioned.

579
00:39:16,770 --> 00:39:19,470
So that bias is
called position bias.

580
00:39:19,470 --> 00:39:23,610
So it's where the position at
which you place the response

581
00:39:23,610 --> 00:39:31,690
matters in the judgment of
the LLM-as-a-Judge model.

582
00:39:31,690 --> 00:39:36,010
And I guess, as a way
to remedy that, people

583
00:39:36,010 --> 00:39:37,450
have different techniques.

584
00:39:37,450 --> 00:39:42,160
But one typical technique
would be to ask the model,

585
00:39:42,160 --> 00:39:44,040
is A or B better?

586
00:39:44,040 --> 00:39:48,280
And then ask the model,
is B or A better?

587
00:39:48,280 --> 00:39:50,460
And then take the
majority voting.

588
00:39:50,460 --> 00:39:56,160
So if both of them lead to the
same response, then it's good.

589
00:39:56,160 --> 00:39:59,940
But if the response changes,
then it may not be good.

590
00:39:59,940 --> 00:40:01,910
So you may want to
do something else.

591
00:40:05,680 --> 00:40:07,500
There are a bunch
of other techniques.

592
00:40:07,500 --> 00:40:09,040
So I know there's
a bunch of papers

593
00:40:09,040 --> 00:40:11,780
that try to tweak the
position embeddings,

594
00:40:11,780 --> 00:40:14,053
but those ones are
a bit more advanced.

595
00:40:14,053 --> 00:40:15,720
So it's not typically
the thing that you

596
00:40:15,720 --> 00:40:18,200
would do just out of the box.

597
00:40:18,200 --> 00:40:21,640
So taking the average
or taking the majority

598
00:40:21,640 --> 00:40:25,900
voting of this position swapping
is typically what you would do.

599
00:40:29,160 --> 00:40:29,660
Cool.

600
00:40:29,660 --> 00:40:31,300
So this was the
first kind of bias.

601
00:40:31,300 --> 00:40:35,920
The second bias is
called verbosity bias.

602
00:40:35,920 --> 00:40:39,520
So let's suppose you
have two responses.

603
00:40:39,520 --> 00:40:44,480
And the first response
is short and concise.

604
00:40:44,480 --> 00:40:46,560
The second response
is something that

605
00:40:46,560 --> 00:40:49,120
goes much more into
details, is typically

606
00:40:49,120 --> 00:40:51,480
something that is more verbose.

607
00:40:51,480 --> 00:40:59,520
Well, there are cases where the
model will tend to, I guess,

608
00:40:59,520 --> 00:41:01,898
prefer responses that are
just more verbose just

609
00:41:01,898 --> 00:41:04,440
because they're more verbose,
not necessarily because they're

610
00:41:04,440 --> 00:41:07,200
more correct.

611
00:41:07,200 --> 00:41:10,420
And for that, it's maybe
a little bit trickier.

612
00:41:10,420 --> 00:41:17,200
So people typically try
to explicit this dimension

613
00:41:17,200 --> 00:41:19,160
in the guidelines.

614
00:41:19,160 --> 00:41:25,660
When they input, I guess, this
question to the LLM-as-a-Judge,

615
00:41:25,660 --> 00:41:28,880
they say, well, make sure to
not pay too much attention

616
00:41:28,880 --> 00:41:32,500
to the length of these
responses to not, I guess,

617
00:41:32,500 --> 00:41:35,840
prefer something just
because it's more verbose.

618
00:41:35,840 --> 00:41:40,640
So that's one kind of method
that you will see out there.

619
00:41:40,640 --> 00:41:43,520
The second one is
to just also add

620
00:41:43,520 --> 00:41:46,960
some examples, in-context
learning examples,

621
00:41:46,960 --> 00:41:52,592
to the model to just,
I guess, tell it to,

622
00:41:52,592 --> 00:41:55,960
I guess, show by example
that verbosity is not

623
00:41:55,960 --> 00:41:58,260
something you should prefer.

624
00:41:58,260 --> 00:42:04,600
And then the last one is to
have some kind of penalty

625
00:42:04,600 --> 00:42:07,080
on the output length.

626
00:42:07,080 --> 00:42:10,480
So you can ask your
model in a pointwise way,

627
00:42:10,480 --> 00:42:13,560
how good is 1, how good is 2.

628
00:42:13,560 --> 00:42:17,280
And then try to penalize
that with the length.

629
00:42:17,280 --> 00:42:21,640
So that's something that
also people may use.

630
00:42:21,640 --> 00:42:24,140
So we've seen position bias.

631
00:42:24,140 --> 00:42:26,420
We've seen verbosity bias.

632
00:42:26,420 --> 00:42:28,040
Now we will see the
third kind of bias

633
00:42:28,040 --> 00:42:29,540
that you may see
out there, which is

634
00:42:29,540 --> 00:42:34,200
called self-enhancement bias.

635
00:42:34,200 --> 00:42:37,750
And so that one has
to do with the fact

636
00:42:37,750 --> 00:42:45,630
that if you ask a model to judge
an output that was produced

637
00:42:45,630 --> 00:42:50,390
by itself, well,
the model will tend

638
00:42:50,390 --> 00:42:55,510
to prefer responses that are
generated by itself, regardless

639
00:42:55,510 --> 00:42:58,900
of whether or not the
other one was more

640
00:42:58,900 --> 00:43:03,270
aligned with what we wanted.

641
00:43:03,270 --> 00:43:05,990
And I guess, here
the intuition is

642
00:43:05,990 --> 00:43:11,270
that if our model
generated such an answer,

643
00:43:11,270 --> 00:43:16,270
then it may be the case
that our model thought that

644
00:43:16,270 --> 00:43:18,430
from a probabilistic
standpoint, this

645
00:43:18,430 --> 00:43:22,910
was a sequence that was
very much likely to appear.

646
00:43:22,910 --> 00:43:25,390
So it may be, I guess,
one way to think

647
00:43:25,390 --> 00:43:29,050
about it, which is, if it has
generated such a sequence,

648
00:43:29,050 --> 00:43:35,250
then it means that it is
something that it thinks--

649
00:43:35,250 --> 00:43:41,230
I mean, "think," quote, unquote,
that it's a good answer.

650
00:43:41,230 --> 00:43:44,510
So the general guideline
here is to typically not use

651
00:43:44,510 --> 00:43:52,070
the same model that you use
for generation and for judges.

652
00:43:52,070 --> 00:43:56,910
But I guess nowadays,
it's hard to have

653
00:43:56,910 --> 00:44:03,270
that strict
constraints, I guess,

654
00:44:03,270 --> 00:44:06,510
respected because, I
guess, all models, they

655
00:44:06,510 --> 00:44:10,430
are trained on basically
the same data sets.

656
00:44:10,430 --> 00:44:15,130
So you can argue they're all
being subject to the same,

657
00:44:15,130 --> 00:44:18,270
I guess, training
mixes and so on.

658
00:44:18,270 --> 00:44:20,750
But still, I guess,
what people do

659
00:44:20,750 --> 00:44:25,870
is they tend to use
another model just to have

660
00:44:25,870 --> 00:44:28,310
such a risk be minimized.

661
00:44:28,310 --> 00:44:31,910
So long story short, try to
not use the exact same model

662
00:44:31,910 --> 00:44:36,360
that you use for generation
and for evaluation.

663
00:44:39,220 --> 00:44:40,930
So this is
self-enhancement bias.

664
00:44:43,500 --> 00:44:46,460
Before we go to
the next subpart,

665
00:44:46,460 --> 00:44:49,080
I guess, what do you think
of these three biases?

666
00:44:49,080 --> 00:44:50,460
Do they make sense?

667
00:44:50,460 --> 00:44:53,360
Any questions so far?

668
00:44:53,360 --> 00:44:53,860
Yep.

669
00:45:03,220 --> 00:45:04,600
So can you elaborate a bit more?

670
00:45:14,880 --> 00:45:18,660
So the question is, can you
have a model that just maybe

671
00:45:18,660 --> 00:45:21,540
isn't aligned with, I
guess, the ground truth

672
00:45:21,540 --> 00:45:24,840
and maybe prioritizes maybe
one label over another?

673
00:45:24,840 --> 00:45:27,980
So this can definitely
be another kind of bias,

674
00:45:27,980 --> 00:45:32,180
so this bias being that our
LLM is not exactly aligned

675
00:45:32,180 --> 00:45:34,860
with what humans would prefer.

676
00:45:34,860 --> 00:45:38,500
So these three biases are
by no means exhaustive.

677
00:45:38,500 --> 00:45:43,540
So this can very well be another
bias that you can list as well.

678
00:45:43,540 --> 00:45:46,840
This is definitely
another kind of bias.

679
00:45:46,840 --> 00:45:47,340
Yep.

680
00:46:00,020 --> 00:46:02,260
So the question
is, is it possible

681
00:46:02,260 --> 00:46:05,440
that our judge still
prefers an LLM response,

682
00:46:05,440 --> 00:46:06,860
even if it's a different one?

683
00:46:06,860 --> 00:46:10,020
Well, it depends how
good your judge is.

684
00:46:10,020 --> 00:46:12,740
But typically, the
best practice is

685
00:46:12,740 --> 00:46:17,460
to have a judge that has a
much bigger capacity that

686
00:46:17,460 --> 00:46:20,420
may capture this
kind of differences

687
00:46:20,420 --> 00:46:24,460
and not be fooled by a
response that just sounds

688
00:46:24,460 --> 00:46:27,140
like something it may
generate but something

689
00:46:27,140 --> 00:46:30,700
that is maybe more aligned
with human preferences.

690
00:46:30,700 --> 00:46:33,060
So I guess the short answer
is yes, you can still

691
00:46:33,060 --> 00:46:34,580
have such a situation.

692
00:46:34,580 --> 00:46:37,420
But in order to
mitigate that risk,

693
00:46:37,420 --> 00:46:39,620
you would typically
take a model that

694
00:46:39,620 --> 00:46:43,540
is not the same but also
typically much bigger.

695
00:46:43,540 --> 00:46:47,720
So you have a bunch of
such models out there.

696
00:46:47,720 --> 00:46:52,180
And with all the, I
guess, improvements

697
00:46:52,180 --> 00:46:53,985
that have been made
with reasoning models,

698
00:46:53,985 --> 00:46:55,610
this is also something
that people try.

699
00:47:01,340 --> 00:47:04,020
Question is, should
the judge be bigger?

700
00:47:04,020 --> 00:47:06,060
It's not a hard constraint,
but it's typically

701
00:47:06,060 --> 00:47:07,680
something that
people would take,

702
00:47:07,680 --> 00:47:11,180
a bigger model that would
have a strong reasoning

703
00:47:11,180 --> 00:47:14,660
capabilities that could
really tease out what's good

704
00:47:14,660 --> 00:47:15,720
and what's not good.

705
00:47:19,880 --> 00:47:21,020
Cool.

706
00:47:21,020 --> 00:47:24,900
So with that, I'm going to
just go over the best practices

707
00:47:24,900 --> 00:47:26,315
that we've seen.

708
00:47:26,315 --> 00:47:32,370
So we saw that in order for
our LLM-as-a-Judge to output

709
00:47:32,370 --> 00:47:37,170
a score, we need to give the
criteria that we want this to be

710
00:47:37,170 --> 00:47:38,930
evaluated against.

711
00:47:38,930 --> 00:47:43,010
But sometimes these criteria
may be a little bit subjective.

712
00:47:43,010 --> 00:47:47,050
So one thing that
really works very well

713
00:47:47,050 --> 00:47:53,090
is to have crisp guidelines, so
really explicit what we want,

714
00:47:53,090 --> 00:47:53,980
what we don't want.

715
00:47:57,090 --> 00:48:01,170
The other point is you may
see different kinds of scaling

716
00:48:01,170 --> 00:48:05,490
out there, so sometimes
people having a scale that

717
00:48:05,490 --> 00:48:09,530
is maybe more granular and maybe
other cases where we're just

718
00:48:09,530 --> 00:48:12,010
operating on a binary scale.

719
00:48:12,010 --> 00:48:17,010
So typically, what people would
tend to prefer is actually

720
00:48:17,010 --> 00:48:22,570
the binary one because it makes
the job of the LLM-as-a-Judge

721
00:48:22,570 --> 00:48:23,110
easier.

722
00:48:23,110 --> 00:48:26,970
So it's just either good or bad.

723
00:48:26,970 --> 00:48:31,210
And also, when it comes
to aligning the judge

724
00:48:31,210 --> 00:48:35,970
with human ratings,
humans, they typically also

725
00:48:35,970 --> 00:48:40,210
find it easier to just
judge out of two options,

726
00:48:40,210 --> 00:48:42,170
as opposed to several.

727
00:48:42,170 --> 00:48:47,390
So it just removes the noise of
having several possible choices.

728
00:48:47,390 --> 00:48:50,130
And it's not necessarily
an extra signal

729
00:48:50,130 --> 00:48:53,130
that may be really useful.

730
00:48:53,130 --> 00:48:58,250
So here the tip is to use
a binary scale, like a pass

731
00:48:58,250 --> 00:49:03,810
or fail kind of score, as
opposed to a gradual one.

732
00:49:03,810 --> 00:49:06,810
The third tip is to
make sure to output

733
00:49:06,810 --> 00:49:10,930
the rationale before
outputting the score.

734
00:49:10,930 --> 00:49:15,690
And we've seen this is along
the same ideas of outputting

735
00:49:15,690 --> 00:49:18,050
a chain of thought before
providing the response, which

736
00:49:18,050 --> 00:49:21,170
is something that is done
by our reasoning models.

737
00:49:21,170 --> 00:49:24,650
So it's typically
something that will improve

738
00:49:24,650 --> 00:49:27,330
the judge's performance.

739
00:49:27,330 --> 00:49:29,910
So we've talked about the
different kinds of biases.

740
00:49:29,910 --> 00:49:33,470
So position, verbosity,
self-enhancement.

741
00:49:33,470 --> 00:49:35,350
But it's not the
only ones, of course.

742
00:49:35,350 --> 00:49:39,490
And I guess, people
typically also

743
00:49:39,490 --> 00:49:42,690
look at how to mitigate
those with the remedies

744
00:49:42,690 --> 00:49:45,890
that we mentioned.

745
00:49:45,890 --> 00:49:50,930
So far, we've stated
that we do not need

746
00:49:50,930 --> 00:49:54,010
human ratings to get started.

747
00:49:54,010 --> 00:49:56,730
But a good practice
is to still look

748
00:49:56,730 --> 00:50:03,770
at how the LLM ratings compare
with the human ratings.

749
00:50:03,770 --> 00:50:07,410
So here one tip is to just
calibrate the responses

750
00:50:07,410 --> 00:50:10,930
that the judge is giving with
respect to the human ratings

751
00:50:10,930 --> 00:50:14,450
because at the end of the day,
it is the quantity that we

752
00:50:14,450 --> 00:50:16,970
want to approximate.

753
00:50:16,970 --> 00:50:20,650
And so here, I guess, if there
is the budget and it's something

754
00:50:20,650 --> 00:50:23,360
that is possible
for the project,

755
00:50:23,360 --> 00:50:28,760
one good practice is to
collect the human ratings,

756
00:50:28,760 --> 00:50:31,380
output the
LLM-as-a-Judge scores,

757
00:50:31,380 --> 00:50:34,600
and then run some correlation
analysis to see if there is

758
00:50:34,600 --> 00:50:38,740
something that can be improved
in terms of the prompt,

759
00:50:38,740 --> 00:50:41,720
mainly the prompt.

760
00:50:41,720 --> 00:50:45,760
And then the last thing
is the temperature.

761
00:50:45,760 --> 00:50:49,600
So if you remember,
the temperature

762
00:50:49,600 --> 00:50:52,800
is a parameter
that you can tweak

763
00:50:52,800 --> 00:50:58,360
to make your generation more
deterministic as opposed

764
00:50:58,360 --> 00:51:00,280
to more creative.

765
00:51:00,280 --> 00:51:03,440
And so you will see that
for evaluation tasks,

766
00:51:03,440 --> 00:51:06,960
people use a low
temperature because they

767
00:51:06,960 --> 00:51:11,680
want to make their evaluation
experiments reproducible.

768
00:51:11,680 --> 00:51:14,240
Let's imagine you
do one evaluation,

769
00:51:14,240 --> 00:51:17,360
and then you do
another one, let's say,

770
00:51:17,360 --> 00:51:20,000
two days later, you
don't want the scores

771
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:21,880
to be super different.

772
00:51:21,880 --> 00:51:24,520
So you will see a temperature
value of something

773
00:51:24,520 --> 00:51:26,360
like 0.1 or 0.2.

774
00:51:26,360 --> 00:51:32,200
These are very common
values that people take.

775
00:51:32,200 --> 00:51:35,800
And so long story short,
if we were to recap,

776
00:51:35,800 --> 00:51:42,360
we went from the ideal scenario
being that each LLM output is

777
00:51:42,360 --> 00:51:49,280
rated by humans to
actually having some kind

778
00:51:49,280 --> 00:51:53,560
of approximation with these
LLM-as-a-Judge models that can

779
00:51:53,560 --> 00:51:58,960
do this evaluation, I guess,
without any constraints

780
00:51:58,960 --> 00:52:03,120
or without any need
for human judgments.

781
00:52:03,120 --> 00:52:07,280
But as we mentioned
in the best practices,

782
00:52:07,280 --> 00:52:11,320
making sure that the
LLM-as-a-Judge scores

783
00:52:11,320 --> 00:52:16,120
and the human ratings do not
diverge is something that we

784
00:52:16,120 --> 00:52:21,710
should keep in mind as we
improve our model because it may

785
00:52:21,710 --> 00:52:26,150
be that we're improving our
model so that our LLM-as-a-Judge

786
00:52:26,150 --> 00:52:31,270
score is very high, but the
LLM-as-a-Judge score is itself

787
00:52:31,270 --> 00:52:33,610
an approximation
of human ratings.

788
00:52:33,610 --> 00:52:38,370
So I guess you don't want to
overoptimize against, I guess,

789
00:52:38,370 --> 00:52:39,010
the proxy.

790
00:52:39,010 --> 00:52:43,630
And so that's why you want to
have that proxy be as aligned

791
00:52:43,630 --> 00:52:47,030
as possible with
your ground truth

792
00:52:47,030 --> 00:52:48,600
labels, which are human ratings.

793
00:52:52,170 --> 00:52:53,670
Cool.

794
00:52:53,670 --> 00:52:57,970
So we have a few minutes left
before giving it to Shervine.

795
00:52:57,970 --> 00:53:03,270
So I'm going to quickly go
over the kinds of dimensions

796
00:53:03,270 --> 00:53:08,230
that people measure
LLM output against.

797
00:53:08,230 --> 00:53:11,410
So we have broadly-- so
there are many dimensions,

798
00:53:11,410 --> 00:53:14,190
but just to simplify
things, there

799
00:53:14,190 --> 00:53:16,970
are two main dimensions
that we can look at here.

800
00:53:16,970 --> 00:53:21,490
So one is how well your
task is being done,

801
00:53:21,490 --> 00:53:27,010
so task performance with things
like, was the response useful,

802
00:53:27,010 --> 00:53:31,150
was the response factual,
was the response relevant,

803
00:53:31,150 --> 00:53:33,270
among other things.

804
00:53:33,270 --> 00:53:39,430
And also, how aligned
was the response format

805
00:53:39,430 --> 00:53:44,270
in terms of tone, in terms of
whether the style was something

806
00:53:44,270 --> 00:53:45,910
that is aligned
with what we want,

807
00:53:45,910 --> 00:53:51,470
in terms of whether there was
any unsafe elements of response

808
00:53:51,470 --> 00:53:54,470
that was given to the user?

809
00:53:54,470 --> 00:53:58,670
And I just want us to
spend maybe five minutes

810
00:53:58,670 --> 00:54:02,190
on the factory dimension,
which is actually

811
00:54:02,190 --> 00:54:06,550
something that requires
a little bit more work.

812
00:54:06,550 --> 00:54:10,430
And I'll give you
just a setting.

813
00:54:10,430 --> 00:54:15,990
So let's suppose we
have some text output,

814
00:54:15,990 --> 00:54:21,430
and our goal is to quantify
how factual that output is.

815
00:54:21,430 --> 00:54:23,990
So I'm going to read
the text out loud.

816
00:54:23,990 --> 00:54:27,090
Teddy bears, first
created in the 1920s,

817
00:54:27,090 --> 00:54:29,870
were named after President
Theodore Roosevelt after he

818
00:54:29,870 --> 00:54:33,750
proudly wanted to shoot a
captured bear on a hunting trip.

819
00:54:33,750 --> 00:54:41,030
So what we want is quantify how
factual that piece of text is.

820
00:54:41,030 --> 00:54:48,270
So I told you previously that we
typically prefer binary scales

821
00:54:48,270 --> 00:54:52,030
when it comes to rating
something with respect

822
00:54:52,030 --> 00:54:54,470
to a dimension.

823
00:54:54,470 --> 00:55:00,430
But the thing with factuality
is that there's a lot of nuance.

824
00:55:00,430 --> 00:55:03,050
Some texts may be very wrong.

825
00:55:03,050 --> 00:55:04,650
Some texts may be
a little bit wrong.

826
00:55:04,650 --> 00:55:07,350
Some texts may be
not wrong at all.

827
00:55:07,350 --> 00:55:12,060
So we want to capture
how wrong the text is,

828
00:55:12,060 --> 00:55:17,040
given the fact that the text
can contain a lot of sentences.

829
00:55:17,040 --> 00:55:20,100
And if there's one
small issue, we

830
00:55:20,100 --> 00:55:25,940
don't want to just say the
whole thing was not correct.

831
00:55:25,940 --> 00:55:27,800
So I'm not sure if
you saw in this text,

832
00:55:27,800 --> 00:55:30,460
but there are
actually two errors.

833
00:55:30,460 --> 00:55:34,420
So it's not 1920s but 1900s
that the teddy bears were first

834
00:55:34,420 --> 00:55:35,060
created.

835
00:55:35,060 --> 00:55:39,780
And the president didn't
want to proudly shoot.

836
00:55:39,780 --> 00:55:41,980
He actually, I think, refused.

837
00:55:41,980 --> 00:55:45,540
So if we are in such
a case, the question

838
00:55:45,540 --> 00:55:48,420
that we want to
tackle here is how

839
00:55:48,420 --> 00:55:51,570
do we want to
quantify this nuance.

840
00:55:54,100 --> 00:55:56,780
So this is an open
question that people

841
00:55:56,780 --> 00:55:59,900
have been writing papers on.

842
00:55:59,900 --> 00:56:02,700
So what I'm going
to tell you now

843
00:56:02,700 --> 00:56:06,740
is something that people
typically use nowadays based

844
00:56:06,740 --> 00:56:10,700
on research that has been done.

845
00:56:10,700 --> 00:56:16,020
So we typically
operate in a few steps.

846
00:56:16,020 --> 00:56:23,500
So the first step is for us to
go from the original text output

847
00:56:23,500 --> 00:56:29,260
to a list of facts because
when you look at a text,

848
00:56:29,260 --> 00:56:33,220
it actually contains a lot of
facts that need to be checked.

849
00:56:33,220 --> 00:56:40,060
And so the idea here is to
aggregate the factuality

850
00:56:40,060 --> 00:56:44,620
of this text along the
dimension of the facts

851
00:56:44,620 --> 00:56:47,620
that are present in this text.

852
00:56:47,620 --> 00:56:51,500
So in this example, we
would have one LLM call

853
00:56:51,500 --> 00:56:56,500
that transforms our original
multi-sentence, multi-paragraph

854
00:56:56,500 --> 00:57:02,740
potentially text
into a list of facts.

855
00:57:02,740 --> 00:57:07,180
So here in this example,
we would have four facts.

856
00:57:07,180 --> 00:57:09,060
So that's the first step.

857
00:57:09,060 --> 00:57:13,340
The second step is we would
go over each of these facts

858
00:57:13,340 --> 00:57:18,060
and check whether it
is correct or not.

859
00:57:18,060 --> 00:57:23,140
And so here, we would typically
proceed in a binary fashion

860
00:57:23,140 --> 00:57:27,620
because if you think about it,
a fact is either correct or not.

861
00:57:27,620 --> 00:57:29,560
I mean, you may have
some in between,

862
00:57:29,560 --> 00:57:35,060
but we don't want to
overcomplicate the task.

863
00:57:35,060 --> 00:57:38,580
And so here the
fact-checking process

864
00:57:38,580 --> 00:57:41,580
would typically involve
the other technique

865
00:57:41,580 --> 00:57:46,460
we've seen last lecture,
like RAG, for instance.

866
00:57:46,460 --> 00:57:50,580
Given a piece of text,
we want to, I guess,

867
00:57:50,580 --> 00:57:53,380
query a knowledge base
with the actual fact

868
00:57:53,380 --> 00:57:56,140
and then check whether
the fact that it's here

869
00:57:56,140 --> 00:57:57,900
is actually correct.

870
00:57:57,900 --> 00:58:00,060
So this fact-checking
process is typically

871
00:58:00,060 --> 00:58:03,780
something that involves
things like RAG,

872
00:58:03,780 --> 00:58:09,250
web search is also
something else, and so on.

873
00:58:09,250 --> 00:58:12,250
So you can think of
this fact-checking step

874
00:58:12,250 --> 00:58:17,930
as also involving LLM calls.

875
00:58:17,930 --> 00:58:25,530
And so you can also think of
some facts being more important

876
00:58:25,530 --> 00:58:27,650
than others.

877
00:58:27,650 --> 00:58:31,570
So as an example, maybe the
fact that the president proudly

878
00:58:31,570 --> 00:58:36,070
wanted to shoot the bear is
not as important as, let's say,

879
00:58:36,070 --> 00:58:39,690
the name of the person
after which the teddy bears

880
00:58:39,690 --> 00:58:40,530
were named.

881
00:58:40,530 --> 00:58:46,010
So you can think of also
having weights that quantifies

882
00:58:46,010 --> 00:58:49,490
the importance of each fact.

883
00:58:49,490 --> 00:58:55,010
So people would use something
like this formula, which

884
00:58:55,010 --> 00:59:00,330
is an aggregation over all the
facts with some weight that

885
00:59:00,330 --> 00:59:03,490
quantifies the
importance of each fact.

886
00:59:03,490 --> 00:59:09,030
So these weights, alpha i, can
be all equal to one another

887
00:59:09,030 --> 00:59:11,010
if you want to make it simpler.

888
00:59:11,010 --> 00:59:14,690
It's not something that
is necessarily the case

889
00:59:14,690 --> 00:59:17,070
everywhere that these
must be different.

890
00:59:17,070 --> 00:59:20,690
But it may be something
that you can tweak.

891
00:59:20,690 --> 00:59:24,450
So if we go back to our
initial question, which is,

892
00:59:24,450 --> 00:59:28,330
how do you quantify the
factuality of this text?

893
00:59:28,330 --> 00:59:32,210
Here you would
say, OK, the second

894
00:59:32,210 --> 00:59:35,730
and the third facts
are both correct.

895
00:59:35,730 --> 00:59:38,290
We know how important they are.

896
00:59:38,290 --> 00:59:41,810
So we run this
aggregation formula,

897
00:59:41,810 --> 00:59:45,522
and we obtain a score of 0.6.

898
00:59:45,522 --> 00:59:47,230
So that means that
there are some errors.

899
00:59:47,230 --> 00:59:49,770
But we still have
some things that

900
00:59:49,770 --> 00:59:52,970
were still factually correct.

901
00:59:52,970 --> 00:59:58,738
This is typically how you would
run this criteria with, I guess,

902
00:59:58,738 --> 01:00:00,280
the techniques that
we have nowadays.

903
01:00:02,840 --> 01:00:03,340
Cool.

904
01:00:03,340 --> 01:00:04,380
I know I'm two minutes late.

905
01:00:04,380 --> 01:00:06,430
And with that, I'm going
to give it to Shervine.

906
01:00:09,680 --> 01:00:11,520
Thank you, Afshine.

907
01:00:11,520 --> 01:00:15,380
So before we move on to
looking at specific benchmarks,

908
01:00:15,380 --> 01:00:18,000
I wanted to take
a detour and look

909
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:22,440
at what is happening on
the agent side of things.

910
01:00:22,440 --> 01:00:27,120
So if you recall what we
discussed last lecture,

911
01:00:27,120 --> 01:00:29,680
we talked about
this ReAct framework

912
01:00:29,680 --> 01:00:35,000
where you could decompose what
was going on within an agent

913
01:00:35,000 --> 01:00:37,600
into specific steps.

914
01:00:37,600 --> 01:00:40,060
So it's usually three steps.

915
01:00:40,060 --> 01:00:44,640
It can be observe, plan, act,
or it can have other names.

916
01:00:44,640 --> 01:00:49,160
But the fact is that you have
several atomic steps that

917
01:00:49,160 --> 01:00:51,040
can loop.

918
01:00:51,040 --> 01:00:57,040
So if you take a look at the
typical agent's inner working,

919
01:00:57,040 --> 01:01:00,160
you can see a pattern like this.

920
01:01:00,160 --> 01:01:04,840
Now you might wonder, how do
you even evaluate such a thing.

921
01:01:04,840 --> 01:01:11,080
So let's take a look
at just one loop.

922
01:01:11,080 --> 01:01:15,080
And then let's see together
what can the errors be,

923
01:01:15,080 --> 01:01:19,280
in order for us to have an idea
of what would an evaluation

924
01:01:19,280 --> 01:01:23,360
result mean on an
agentic workflow.

925
01:01:23,360 --> 01:01:30,160
So I'm going to show a
slide that we had presented

926
01:01:30,160 --> 01:01:31,920
at the previous lecture.

927
01:01:31,920 --> 01:01:37,040
And we had seen that
we can decompose a tool

928
01:01:37,040 --> 01:01:40,320
call into these three steps.

929
01:01:40,320 --> 01:01:43,480
So let's take our
favorite example.

930
01:01:43,480 --> 01:01:46,340
Let's say, you want to
find a bear near you.

931
01:01:46,340 --> 01:01:48,360
So you would ask
that to the model.

932
01:01:48,360 --> 01:01:52,040
So the first stage is
to find the right tool

933
01:01:52,040 --> 01:01:55,280
call with the right argument.

934
01:01:55,280 --> 01:01:58,960
And then once you have
found this right tool call,

935
01:01:58,960 --> 01:02:00,960
you need to execute it.

936
01:02:00,960 --> 01:02:04,320
And then based on your
tool call prediction

937
01:02:04,320 --> 01:02:08,400
and on the results that you
obtained from your tool,

938
01:02:08,400 --> 01:02:12,240
you would infer the
results at the last step.

939
01:02:12,240 --> 01:02:14,240
So these are three steps.

940
01:02:14,240 --> 01:02:17,280
And you might have
a series of them

941
01:02:17,280 --> 01:02:19,200
in the case of an
agentic workflow

942
01:02:19,200 --> 01:02:23,480
where you call multiple tools
and then build up your reasoning

943
01:02:23,480 --> 01:02:26,330
until reaching an answer that
you then give to the user.

944
01:02:29,480 --> 01:02:36,200
So now let's look at what can
the failure modes, what can they

945
01:02:36,200 --> 01:02:38,480
be, at each of these steps.

946
01:02:38,480 --> 01:02:44,200
So first, let's take a look at
possible tool prediction errors.

947
01:02:44,200 --> 01:02:47,040
So the first one
I want to mention

948
01:02:47,040 --> 01:02:52,040
is the case where the error
is that from a user query

949
01:02:52,040 --> 01:02:56,310
that obviously needs a tool,
that you don't actually

950
01:02:56,310 --> 01:02:57,790
use the tool.

951
01:02:57,790 --> 01:03:02,430
So here let's suppose that
if you want to find a bear,

952
01:03:02,430 --> 01:03:07,150
you have the tool to find bears
at-hand, but you don't use it.

953
01:03:07,150 --> 01:03:09,070
So typically, if
you don't use it,

954
01:03:09,070 --> 01:03:15,190
a possible behavior from the
model can be to say an error.

955
01:03:15,190 --> 01:03:19,690
So an error-- by an error, I
mean, sorry, I cannot do that.

956
01:03:19,690 --> 01:03:24,190
And this, in assistant terms,
you can call this a punt.

957
01:03:24,190 --> 01:03:27,350
So when you don't answer
the question, you just fail.

958
01:03:27,350 --> 01:03:28,710
It's called a punt.

959
01:03:28,710 --> 01:03:29,910
So you might punt.

960
01:03:29,910 --> 01:03:33,390
Here, sorry, I don't
where I can find one.

961
01:03:33,390 --> 01:03:37,870
And let's see together what
could possibly cause this issue

962
01:03:37,870 --> 01:03:42,030
and how we could remedy it.

963
01:03:42,030 --> 01:03:45,670
So I don't know if you recall
the concept of tool router

964
01:03:45,670 --> 01:03:48,630
or tool selector that
we had introduced.

965
01:03:48,630 --> 01:03:51,590
So usually, when you
are dealing with tools,

966
01:03:51,590 --> 01:03:53,070
you don't have just one.

967
01:03:53,070 --> 01:03:55,150
You have multiple ones.

968
01:03:55,150 --> 01:03:57,110
And the number of
tools that might

969
01:03:57,110 --> 01:04:02,230
be useful for a large scale in
the sense of number of users

970
01:04:02,230 --> 01:04:05,110
LLM, might be large.

971
01:04:05,110 --> 01:04:10,550
So you don't want to input all
the function APIs at every call.

972
01:04:10,550 --> 01:04:14,070
So it might be the case that
you have this intermediary step,

973
01:04:14,070 --> 01:04:18,390
where you filter down the
sets of possible functions

974
01:04:18,390 --> 01:04:21,390
that you can put
in the preamble.

975
01:04:21,390 --> 01:04:27,070
And here these two
selectors or tool routers,

976
01:04:27,070 --> 01:04:31,710
they have the property of
trying to be recall-oriented.

977
01:04:31,710 --> 01:04:34,870
So you want to trim
the list of functions

978
01:04:34,870 --> 01:04:38,630
that you want to
input in the preamble.

979
01:04:38,630 --> 01:04:42,390
But you want to at least
find those that you need.

980
01:04:42,390 --> 01:04:44,110
So the main property
here is that you

981
01:04:44,110 --> 01:04:49,070
want to save on context
space, but you still

982
01:04:49,070 --> 01:04:54,470
want to ensure most of your
use cases are still working.

983
01:04:54,470 --> 01:04:59,070
So this is why here, when
we say tool router error,

984
01:04:59,070 --> 01:05:01,670
we actually mean a recall error.

985
01:05:01,670 --> 01:05:03,910
So it means it's
possible that we just

986
01:05:03,910 --> 01:05:07,950
didn't select the right
tool among the set of tools.

987
01:05:07,950 --> 01:05:10,490
And let's say,
this is the cause.

988
01:05:10,490 --> 01:05:12,910
Then it's pretty
clear we just have

989
01:05:12,910 --> 01:05:15,670
to adjust the tool
router in order

990
01:05:15,670 --> 01:05:19,550
for it to be predicting
the right tool.

991
01:05:19,550 --> 01:05:21,910
So this can be
one kind of issue.

992
01:05:21,910 --> 01:05:25,870
Another kind is, hey,
actually, the tool

993
01:05:25,870 --> 01:05:29,270
was included in this
list of function APIs,

994
01:05:29,270 --> 01:05:35,336
but it's just that the LLM
didn't think about using it.

995
01:05:35,336 --> 01:05:38,210
So maybe this fine
teddy bear was in there,

996
01:05:38,210 --> 01:05:40,530
but we just don't use it.

997
01:05:40,530 --> 01:05:43,550
The LLM directly
outputs a response.

998
01:05:43,550 --> 01:05:46,670
So in that case,
if you recall, we

999
01:05:46,670 --> 01:05:52,140
had mentioned techniques to
teach an LLM to use a tool.

1000
01:05:52,140 --> 01:05:56,140
So you would need to revisit
that part and either--

1001
01:05:56,140 --> 01:06:01,620
if you had trained it with SFT,
so include this pattern maybe

1002
01:06:01,620 --> 01:06:04,780
to train the model
to recognize it,

1003
01:06:04,780 --> 01:06:07,520
or if you had done
prompt tuning,

1004
01:06:07,520 --> 01:06:11,380
then you should revisit your
prompt in order for this call

1005
01:06:11,380 --> 01:06:14,520
to make sense to the model
that you should use that tool.

1006
01:06:17,020 --> 01:06:17,520
Great.

1007
01:06:17,520 --> 01:06:21,780
So this is one kind
of possible error.

1008
01:06:21,780 --> 01:06:24,780
Another one that you
might see in the wild

1009
01:06:24,780 --> 01:06:30,220
when you want to debug agents
is at the time of tool calls,

1010
01:06:30,220 --> 01:06:32,940
it might be the case
that the model comes up

1011
01:06:32,940 --> 01:06:37,420
with a function name that
just simply doesn't exist.

1012
01:06:37,420 --> 01:06:40,280
So here I mentioned
the tool hallucination.

1013
01:06:40,280 --> 01:06:41,860
This is what I mean by that.

1014
01:06:41,860 --> 01:06:46,420
So it calls a function
that is just not defined.

1015
01:06:46,420 --> 01:06:50,920
So here our API was called, if
you remember, find teddy bear.

1016
01:06:50,920 --> 01:06:53,260
So this was the
function that existed.

1017
01:06:53,260 --> 01:06:56,100
And in this example
of failure, the model

1018
01:06:56,100 --> 01:06:59,660
tries to call the
function find_bear, which

1019
01:06:59,660 --> 01:07:01,900
I haven't defined.

1020
01:07:01,900 --> 01:07:08,060
So when you see such errors, you
have several potential causes,

1021
01:07:08,060 --> 01:07:11,700
one of them being
that the model simply

1022
01:07:11,700 --> 01:07:14,540
doesn't round well overall.

1023
01:07:14,540 --> 01:07:21,220
And typically, it occurs
if the model is too simple.

1024
01:07:21,220 --> 01:07:23,200
So it's an empirical
observation.

1025
01:07:23,200 --> 01:07:25,980
If it's too weak, maybe
it can make up things

1026
01:07:25,980 --> 01:07:29,360
that it thinks
can be reasonable.

1027
01:07:29,360 --> 01:07:32,700
But it doesn't actually
ground on your instructions.

1028
01:07:32,700 --> 01:07:36,100
And here I have no
better remedy proposal

1029
01:07:36,100 --> 01:07:38,700
than to maybe upgrade
the model, if you

1030
01:07:38,700 --> 01:07:40,420
see that this is truly
the case, and then

1031
01:07:40,420 --> 01:07:45,620
see if this is reproducible.

1032
01:07:45,620 --> 01:07:48,370
Some other potential
causes could

1033
01:07:48,370 --> 01:07:50,370
be coming from actually you.

1034
01:07:50,370 --> 01:07:53,770
So the model is trained
on very high quality data

1035
01:07:53,770 --> 01:07:56,130
during its SFT stage.

1036
01:07:56,130 --> 01:08:00,570
So it has seen what
great APIs look like.

1037
01:08:00,570 --> 01:08:05,810
So these tools that you define
that help the user achieve what

1038
01:08:05,810 --> 01:08:10,250
they're looking for might not
be written in the best way,

1039
01:08:10,250 --> 01:08:16,210
if you didn't use AI-assistant
coding, let's say, or--

1040
01:08:16,210 --> 01:08:18,290
you don't necessarily
have to use AI-assistant

1041
01:08:18,290 --> 01:08:19,310
coding to write these.

1042
01:08:19,310 --> 01:08:21,569
But these are
typically a great way

1043
01:08:21,569 --> 01:08:24,410
to check whether your
implementation makes sense

1044
01:08:24,410 --> 01:08:26,130
from a model standpoint.

1045
01:08:26,130 --> 01:08:32,170
And if it doesn't, then a
typical remedy is to either--

1046
01:08:32,170 --> 01:08:35,229
renaming the API
just a function name,

1047
01:08:35,229 --> 01:08:38,890
and the arguments
just go a long way

1048
01:08:38,890 --> 01:08:41,649
because this is what
the model will see when

1049
01:08:41,649 --> 01:08:44,170
it comes to your tool call.

1050
01:08:44,170 --> 01:08:47,990
It sees the API function name.

1051
01:08:47,990 --> 01:08:51,290
It sees the arguments and
the high-level descriptions.

1052
01:08:51,290 --> 01:08:54,170
So these are your
three knobs to tune

1053
01:08:54,170 --> 01:08:59,529
in order to make it sound
more logical and then linked

1054
01:08:59,529 --> 01:09:00,689
to the actual task at-hand.

1055
01:09:05,090 --> 01:09:07,250
At the very beginning,
I was saying,

1056
01:09:07,250 --> 01:09:08,830
maybe the model is too weak.

1057
01:09:08,830 --> 01:09:11,490
But actually, maybe the
first thing you should check

1058
01:09:11,490 --> 01:09:14,910
is whether the
horizontal instructions--

1059
01:09:14,910 --> 01:09:19,689
so horizontal across tools,
whether these are clear enough.

1060
01:09:19,689 --> 01:09:24,529
Maybe the model hasn't
really understood

1061
01:09:24,529 --> 01:09:27,470
that it needs to use functions
that are given to it.

1062
01:09:27,470 --> 01:09:30,090
So maybe it's just
making up function names

1063
01:09:30,090 --> 01:09:32,729
that it believes
could have access to.

1064
01:09:32,729 --> 01:09:35,370
So the first thing to
check would probably

1065
01:09:35,370 --> 01:09:40,090
be to see if this
phenomenon is generalized

1066
01:09:40,090 --> 01:09:43,470
and see if these
horizontal instructions,

1067
01:09:43,470 --> 01:09:48,410
they are concisely saying that
you should make sure to use

1068
01:09:48,410 --> 01:09:50,649
available functions.

1069
01:09:50,649 --> 01:09:53,609
And then on that, you can
iterate on these top level

1070
01:09:53,609 --> 01:09:58,570
instructions and maybe
iterate with an LLM

1071
01:09:58,570 --> 01:10:01,750
itself because typically,
top-level instructions,

1072
01:10:01,750 --> 01:10:03,250
they are very important.

1073
01:10:03,250 --> 01:10:07,930
So you need perfect
formatting and perfect logic.

1074
01:10:07,930 --> 01:10:14,190
So typically being able to
detail them with great detail

1075
01:10:14,190 --> 01:10:14,900
is helpful.

1076
01:10:18,370 --> 01:10:22,930
Now let's see a third
possible failure cause.

1077
01:10:22,930 --> 01:10:25,890
So let's say, you
have your model

1078
01:10:25,890 --> 01:10:30,810
and your user prompts, but you
just don't use the right tool.

1079
01:10:30,810 --> 01:10:34,650
So here if the user
says, find a bear near

1080
01:10:34,650 --> 01:10:39,330
me, one other reasonable
approach would be,

1081
01:10:39,330 --> 01:10:44,280
what if you just send a
message asking for a bear?

1082
01:10:44,280 --> 01:10:46,560
That would be reasonable.

1083
01:10:46,560 --> 01:10:50,000
But maybe that's not what
you want to implement

1084
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:52,600
as a behavior for your user.

1085
01:10:52,600 --> 01:10:56,540
So in that case, it's
not clear to the model

1086
01:10:56,540 --> 01:10:58,400
what approach you prefer.

1087
01:10:58,400 --> 01:11:02,000
And it is on your--

1088
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:07,270
it's your responsibility to
ensure it is indeed clear.

1089
01:11:07,270 --> 01:11:11,200
And then you have to do that
at two different levels.

1090
01:11:11,200 --> 01:11:16,520
So the first one is potentially
also at the tool router level.

1091
01:11:16,520 --> 01:11:18,840
Maybe the tool
router doesn't know

1092
01:11:18,840 --> 01:11:21,200
that for this kind
of query, you should

1093
01:11:21,200 --> 01:11:25,560
have the tool that you had in
mind as part of the results.

1094
01:11:25,560 --> 01:11:27,360
So it's possible that
you have a recall

1095
01:11:27,360 --> 01:11:29,680
issue that you need to fix.

1096
01:11:29,680 --> 01:11:32,240
And then the second
one is simply

1097
01:11:32,240 --> 01:11:35,580
going back to the APIs
of both functions,

1098
01:11:35,580 --> 01:11:37,960
maybe the conflicts in scope.

1099
01:11:37,960 --> 01:11:41,360
So you want to go
back to each of them

1100
01:11:41,360 --> 01:11:45,600
and be precise into
which situations should

1101
01:11:45,600 --> 01:11:48,440
be dealt with with which tool.

1102
01:11:48,440 --> 01:11:57,620
So being very precise in these
APIs just plays a lot here.

1103
01:12:00,320 --> 01:12:00,820
Great.

1104
01:12:00,820 --> 01:12:05,920
So now we're going to go through
a fourth and last failure

1105
01:12:05,920 --> 01:12:08,960
mode for this tool
prediction task, which

1106
01:12:08,960 --> 01:12:11,600
is, what if you
have the right tool,

1107
01:12:11,600 --> 01:12:15,400
but you just don't have
the right arguments?

1108
01:12:15,400 --> 01:12:18,040
So you have already
gone one step.

1109
01:12:18,040 --> 01:12:21,280
You have found the right
tool, but then this last mile

1110
01:12:21,280 --> 01:12:25,240
of making sure that the tool
is run with what you would like

1111
01:12:25,240 --> 01:12:26,680
is not fulfilled.

1112
01:12:26,680 --> 01:12:31,360
So here if I say, find a beer
near me, and it outputs--

1113
01:12:31,360 --> 01:12:34,260
and it uses the
coordinates 0, 0,

1114
01:12:34,260 --> 01:12:39,550
which is somewhere in
the Southern Atlantic--

1115
01:12:39,550 --> 01:12:41,750
it's not likely that
I'm actually there,

1116
01:12:41,750 --> 01:12:44,510
that can reflect an issue.

1117
01:12:44,510 --> 01:12:50,350
And one possible
explanation for this

1118
01:12:50,350 --> 01:12:51,870
is that maybe it
simply doesn't know

1119
01:12:51,870 --> 01:12:55,910
where I am because I haven't
specified in my query

1120
01:12:55,910 --> 01:12:58,270
that I'm here at
Stanford, and it just

1121
01:12:58,270 --> 01:13:01,150
tries to make up my coordinates.

1122
01:13:01,150 --> 01:13:05,150
So one thing that you
should double check

1123
01:13:05,150 --> 01:13:09,230
is making sure that the
context carries the location

1124
01:13:09,230 --> 01:13:09,890
information.

1125
01:13:09,890 --> 01:13:13,770
So if I haven't provided that
as a setting on my LLM map,

1126
01:13:13,770 --> 01:13:17,390
it's possible it's not there.

1127
01:13:17,390 --> 01:13:20,170
And then let's say,
if it's not there,

1128
01:13:20,170 --> 01:13:24,230
maybe you would want to
introduce a location finder tool

1129
01:13:24,230 --> 01:13:26,750
that is executed beforehand.

1130
01:13:26,750 --> 01:13:28,550
And if it fails
because I haven't

1131
01:13:28,550 --> 01:13:31,990
given the app to permission
to see my location, then

1132
01:13:31,990 --> 01:13:37,110
maybe you could have actionable
error shown to the user,

1133
01:13:37,110 --> 01:13:41,390
instead of having some
dummy parameters passed in.

1134
01:13:41,390 --> 01:13:44,430
So this is one potential remedy.

1135
01:13:44,430 --> 01:13:48,890
And then the second one is
maybe it's his arguments,

1136
01:13:48,890 --> 01:13:53,150
but the model just doesn't know
what it should put as input.

1137
01:13:53,150 --> 01:13:57,110
So that could also
be another reason.

1138
01:13:57,110 --> 01:14:01,310
And then on that, this
is a common remedy

1139
01:14:01,310 --> 01:14:06,630
to go back and then retrain
either the model on how it uses

1140
01:14:06,630 --> 01:14:09,380
these tools or rewrite the API.

1141
01:14:12,150 --> 01:14:15,630
So we have seen four ways to--

1142
01:14:15,630 --> 01:14:19,050
I mean, four failure modes
for the tool prediction step.

1143
01:14:19,050 --> 01:14:23,240
Now we're going to see two
more on this tool called step.

1144
01:14:26,190 --> 01:14:32,030
So the first one is
a very simple one,

1145
01:14:32,030 --> 01:14:34,550
from a mindset
perspective, maybe

1146
01:14:34,550 --> 01:14:39,430
your tool just doesn't
output the right response.

1147
01:14:39,430 --> 01:14:44,510
So it's a very vague category.

1148
01:14:44,510 --> 01:14:50,670
And as an example, maybe your
code logic has a bug somewhere,

1149
01:14:50,670 --> 01:14:53,730
and it just returns an error.

1150
01:14:53,730 --> 01:14:55,830
Those that you see
in Python, maybe it

1151
01:14:55,830 --> 01:14:59,310
hits some value error
or anything else.

1152
01:14:59,310 --> 01:15:03,150
And I just want to
say that it might not

1153
01:15:03,150 --> 01:15:06,470
be necessarily the case
that hitting an error

1154
01:15:06,470 --> 01:15:12,950
is bad because sometimes in the
case of finding your location,

1155
01:15:12,950 --> 01:15:16,850
if you haven't provided your
permission to find the location,

1156
01:15:16,850 --> 01:15:19,550
maybe it will hit an
error, and the model will

1157
01:15:19,550 --> 01:15:23,470
anchor on that error to
convey the status to the user.

1158
01:15:23,470 --> 01:15:30,310
But in general, it's not really
common practice to return errors

1159
01:15:30,310 --> 01:15:32,940
just because the model
could interpret it

1160
01:15:32,940 --> 01:15:35,080
as an internal tool error.

1161
01:15:35,080 --> 01:15:37,260
So sometimes when
you hit an error,

1162
01:15:37,260 --> 01:15:40,260
and then you ask the
model to synthesize

1163
01:15:40,260 --> 01:15:43,640
the tool call it has seen,
sometimes it just says, oh,

1164
01:15:43,640 --> 01:15:46,160
sorry, I couldn't do
it, but it's my fault.

1165
01:15:46,160 --> 01:15:47,800
It's because I
encountered an error.

1166
01:15:47,800 --> 01:15:52,220
It doesn't really say
actionably what happened.

1167
01:15:52,220 --> 01:15:57,060
And instead, the fix here
is to convey these outputs

1168
01:15:57,060 --> 01:15:58,740
in a meaningful manner.

1169
01:15:58,740 --> 01:16:01,900
So typically, you have
a structured output,

1170
01:16:01,900 --> 01:16:04,440
and you return a true
output instead of an error.

1171
01:16:07,620 --> 01:16:13,060
Here it's a general case just
to say that just check your tool

1172
01:16:13,060 --> 01:16:14,380
implementation.

1173
01:16:14,380 --> 01:16:16,940
So you have the right arguments,
you have the right tool,

1174
01:16:16,940 --> 01:16:19,360
but you just don't
have the right value.

1175
01:16:19,360 --> 01:16:21,420
So just a software
engineering problem,

1176
01:16:21,420 --> 01:16:22,800
just go and fix the tool.

1177
01:16:25,420 --> 01:16:28,340
And the second
category of issues

1178
01:16:28,340 --> 01:16:34,300
that we see at the backend level
is when you return no response.

1179
01:16:34,300 --> 01:16:38,900
And returning no
response is often bad

1180
01:16:38,900 --> 01:16:43,620
when the tool is one
that performs an action.

1181
01:16:43,620 --> 01:16:45,980
So let's say, last
lecture, we talked

1182
01:16:45,980 --> 01:16:49,780
about increasing the
thermostat for your teddy bear

1183
01:16:49,780 --> 01:16:50,720
who was cold.

1184
01:16:50,720 --> 01:16:53,140
So if you increase
the thermostat,

1185
01:16:53,140 --> 01:16:56,060
and the tool doesn't
say anything,

1186
01:16:56,060 --> 01:17:00,100
so the model doesn't know if it
has done the task successfully

1187
01:17:00,100 --> 01:17:01,260
or not.

1188
01:17:01,260 --> 01:17:06,140
So it could well come up with
a false confirmation of hey,

1189
01:17:06,140 --> 01:17:06,720
all is good.

1190
01:17:06,720 --> 01:17:08,460
I have increased the thermostat.

1191
01:17:08,460 --> 01:17:09,780
No worries.

1192
01:17:09,780 --> 01:17:11,980
But it actually hasn't.

1193
01:17:11,980 --> 01:17:16,380
So this is why a common
guidance is to always make sure

1194
01:17:16,380 --> 01:17:21,780
that tool calls are followed
by meaningful outputs.

1195
01:17:21,780 --> 01:17:25,900
So as usual, you have
this structured message

1196
01:17:25,900 --> 01:17:28,900
and you should take
advantage of it

1197
01:17:28,900 --> 01:17:32,460
to convey what has happened
as part of your tool

1198
01:17:32,460 --> 01:17:35,580
in order to make sure
that the model, in turn,

1199
01:17:35,580 --> 01:17:39,420
knows what to convey to
the user or knows how

1200
01:17:39,420 --> 01:17:41,560
to continue that agentic loop.

1201
01:17:45,980 --> 01:17:47,960
So always output something.

1202
01:17:47,960 --> 01:17:51,460
And let's say, you want
to find a teddy bear,

1203
01:17:51,460 --> 01:17:55,380
and you haven't found
any, then here you

1204
01:17:55,380 --> 01:17:57,700
will be surprised by what
I say, but it's actually

1205
01:17:57,700 --> 01:18:03,300
better to output an empty
JSON than just outputting none

1206
01:18:03,300 --> 01:18:07,980
because an empty JSON could
mean I found no bears,

1207
01:18:07,980 --> 01:18:11,220
but an output of none
doesn't say anything.

1208
01:18:11,220 --> 01:18:13,900
So even in that
case, an empty output

1209
01:18:13,900 --> 01:18:17,400
in the sense of an empty
JSON is meaningful.

1210
01:18:17,400 --> 01:18:20,180
And make sure to use that
meaning in the way you

1211
01:18:20,180 --> 01:18:23,260
encode your tool.

1212
01:18:23,260 --> 01:18:23,760
Great.

1213
01:18:23,760 --> 01:18:28,010
So we have seen two
more possible errors

1214
01:18:28,010 --> 01:18:29,730
at the function call level.

1215
01:18:29,730 --> 01:18:33,170
Now let's suppose that
everything went great

1216
01:18:33,170 --> 01:18:34,310
at the first step.

1217
01:18:34,310 --> 01:18:36,610
Everything went great
at the second step.

1218
01:18:36,610 --> 01:18:39,630
So you have found the
right tool output.

1219
01:18:39,630 --> 01:18:44,610
But now the model has trouble
to synthesize the output

1220
01:18:44,610 --> 01:18:46,000
into a meaningful response.

1221
01:18:49,150 --> 01:18:52,550
Let's suppose your tool
found a bear named Teddy.

1222
01:18:52,550 --> 01:18:55,850
And then the other attributes,
which I haven't shown here,

1223
01:18:55,850 --> 01:18:58,530
maybe say that they are
one mile away from me.

1224
01:18:58,530 --> 01:19:00,170
So the teddy bear
has been found,

1225
01:19:00,170 --> 01:19:02,810
and we just have to
present it to the user.

1226
01:19:02,810 --> 01:19:08,450
But if you put it to the model,
let's suppose the model says,

1227
01:19:08,450 --> 01:19:10,410
I didn't find any bear.

1228
01:19:10,410 --> 01:19:12,970
So what could be the cause here?

1229
01:19:12,970 --> 01:19:16,410
So it could be the
case that you have

1230
01:19:16,410 --> 01:19:20,530
an output that has information
that the model doesn't

1231
01:19:20,530 --> 01:19:21,430
ground on.

1232
01:19:21,430 --> 01:19:25,810
So it could be the case that
just the model lacks the ability

1233
01:19:25,810 --> 01:19:31,050
to refer to content
that was put previously.

1234
01:19:31,050 --> 01:19:35,370
So here I have the
same vanilla suggestion

1235
01:19:35,370 --> 01:19:39,530
of upgrading the model.

1236
01:19:39,530 --> 01:19:42,710
So usually, that doesn't
happen really anymore,

1237
01:19:42,710 --> 01:19:46,850
but it used to in early
iterations of LLMs.

1238
01:19:46,850 --> 01:19:52,270
There is one that is actually
one that happens fairly often.

1239
01:19:52,270 --> 01:19:56,250
So sometimes the tool
back end returns not only

1240
01:19:56,250 --> 01:19:58,650
an output but a lot of output.

1241
01:19:58,650 --> 01:20:02,450
And it's too much for the
model to properly parse

1242
01:20:02,450 --> 01:20:04,410
what is important.

1243
01:20:04,410 --> 01:20:06,950
So you have maybe the
information of Teddy in there.

1244
01:20:06,950 --> 01:20:13,930
But it's drowning under an ocean
of other kinds of information

1245
01:20:13,930 --> 01:20:15,510
that are not useful.

1246
01:20:15,510 --> 01:20:19,050
So the model cannot
distinguish what is helpful.

1247
01:20:19,050 --> 01:20:21,010
And then the
solution for that is

1248
01:20:21,010 --> 01:20:23,780
to go back to your
tool implementation

1249
01:20:23,780 --> 01:20:28,360
and ensure that whatever you
output is meaningful to be used

1250
01:20:28,360 --> 01:20:32,600
to the model in the next stage.

1251
01:20:32,600 --> 01:20:35,360
And I think this goes--

1252
01:20:35,360 --> 01:20:38,100
this overlaps with the
third reason I put here.

1253
01:20:38,100 --> 01:20:41,480
So let's say, your output
is trimmed already.

1254
01:20:41,480 --> 01:20:43,720
Then another
possible explanation

1255
01:20:43,720 --> 01:20:47,640
is maybe it's not being
presented in a meaningful way.

1256
01:20:47,640 --> 01:20:50,480
So this is why in Python,
you have these classes where

1257
01:20:50,480 --> 01:20:55,840
you can instantiate attributes
so that the output is

1258
01:20:55,840 --> 01:20:56,980
very meaningful.

1259
01:20:56,980 --> 01:21:01,840
So let's say, for saying
that you have found a bear,

1260
01:21:01,840 --> 01:21:05,440
you could return an
object called teddy bear

1261
01:21:05,440 --> 01:21:08,260
with attribute's name,
distance, and so on--

1262
01:21:08,260 --> 01:21:10,200
this is very
meaningful, as opposed

1263
01:21:10,200 --> 01:21:16,320
to maybe raw information that
it doesn't how to interpret.

1264
01:21:16,320 --> 01:21:16,860
Awesome.

1265
01:21:16,860 --> 01:21:21,360
So we have seen here seven
different failure modes

1266
01:21:21,360 --> 01:21:24,300
over all these categories.

1267
01:21:24,300 --> 01:21:26,640
So these are not the only ones.

1268
01:21:26,640 --> 01:21:30,520
I have just mentioned those that
I see very often that I thought

1269
01:21:30,520 --> 01:21:32,520
could be helpful, but
you could definitely

1270
01:21:32,520 --> 01:21:36,315
see other failure modes.

1271
01:21:36,315 --> 01:21:37,190
Does this make sense?

1272
01:21:40,440 --> 01:21:41,700
Do you have any questions?

1273
01:21:45,960 --> 01:21:46,460
Great.

1274
01:21:46,460 --> 01:21:52,840
So we can move on
to summarizing what

1275
01:21:52,840 --> 01:21:56,540
were the common trends
in these failure modes.

1276
01:21:56,540 --> 01:22:01,240
So oftentimes, we have talked
about the modeling side, where

1277
01:22:01,240 --> 01:22:07,040
sometimes improving the model's
ability to reason and ground

1278
01:22:07,040 --> 01:22:08,030
could be the solution.

1279
01:22:11,000 --> 01:22:13,120
Another complaint
that we have seen

1280
01:22:13,120 --> 01:22:17,200
is the relevance of what we
put in the context window.

1281
01:22:17,200 --> 01:22:20,040
If we improve that relevance,
maybe it gets better.

1282
01:22:20,040 --> 01:22:23,680
And on the modeling
side, one more aspect

1283
01:22:23,680 --> 01:22:26,880
is maybe the tool route's
modeling or the tool

1284
01:22:26,880 --> 01:22:33,800
API modeling itself, either by
SFT tuning or just prompting,

1285
01:22:33,800 --> 01:22:37,000
or even just the API
description itself,

1286
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:39,840
does the function make sense?

1287
01:22:39,840 --> 01:22:42,140
Do the arguments make sense?

1288
01:22:42,140 --> 01:22:44,640
Does the docstring make sense?

1289
01:22:44,640 --> 01:22:46,960
So this is one kind.

1290
01:22:46,960 --> 01:22:50,248
And the other kind
is the tool itself,

1291
01:22:50,248 --> 01:22:51,540
so maybe it just has a problem.

1292
01:22:51,540 --> 01:22:55,120
So you need to fix it.

1293
01:22:55,120 --> 01:22:57,200
And I just want to
say that when you

1294
01:22:57,200 --> 01:22:59,760
deal with tools and
evaluations, you

1295
01:22:59,760 --> 01:23:01,840
have a lot of possible errors.

1296
01:23:01,840 --> 01:23:06,040
So one thing that will help
you to navigate through this

1297
01:23:06,040 --> 01:23:11,480
is to be very methodical into
categorizing kinds of errors

1298
01:23:11,480 --> 01:23:14,720
and then dealing
with them in group.

1299
01:23:14,720 --> 01:23:16,450
So you see there
are lots of errors.

1300
01:23:16,450 --> 01:23:20,070
And every time that you
deal with a given loss,

1301
01:23:20,070 --> 01:23:23,670
it's maybe just an
adventure to solve.

1302
01:23:23,670 --> 01:23:27,210
So really, being very organized
here is going to help you a lot.

1303
01:23:30,470 --> 01:23:37,010
With that in mind, we can delve
into the world of benchmarks.

1304
01:23:37,010 --> 01:23:38,910
So we talked about evaluations.

1305
01:23:38,910 --> 01:23:43,070
Now you might wonder, how can
you evaluate a large language

1306
01:23:43,070 --> 01:23:44,630
model.

1307
01:23:44,630 --> 01:23:46,870
Let's say, you have
trained everything.

1308
01:23:46,870 --> 01:23:49,510
How can you compare it
with respect to others?

1309
01:23:49,510 --> 01:23:56,950
So we're going to see together
a series of benchmark categories

1310
01:23:56,950 --> 01:24:00,710
that today's
benchmarks usually--

1311
01:24:00,710 --> 01:24:04,510
where today's benchmark usually
resides, so in one of these.

1312
01:24:04,510 --> 01:24:07,990
And we're going to see
examples for each of them.

1313
01:24:07,990 --> 01:24:10,550
Does that sound good?

1314
01:24:10,550 --> 01:24:11,070
Awesome.

1315
01:24:11,070 --> 01:24:14,910
So we can start with
a kind of benchmark

1316
01:24:14,910 --> 01:24:19,670
that I called a knowledge-based
benchmark, where

1317
01:24:19,670 --> 01:24:26,920
we want to test if the model is
able to restitute given facts.

1318
01:24:30,770 --> 01:24:35,130
These facts are typically
spanning lots of domains,

1319
01:24:35,130 --> 01:24:39,050
so it doesn't have to be super
precise on a given domain.

1320
01:24:39,050 --> 01:24:41,910
But it's spanning all
the kinds of domains

1321
01:24:41,910 --> 01:24:44,910
that your users may care about.

1322
01:24:44,910 --> 01:24:48,790
And then prime example
for this is MMLU

1323
01:24:48,790 --> 01:24:50,910
that we're going
to see very soon.

1324
01:24:50,910 --> 01:24:54,670
But just before we do so, I
want to say that this knowledge

1325
01:24:54,670 --> 01:25:00,630
benchmark mostly, but not only,
measures how well pretraining

1326
01:25:00,630 --> 01:25:03,510
was done, how well
the information

1327
01:25:03,510 --> 01:25:06,870
in your large
corpora of data was

1328
01:25:06,870 --> 01:25:12,950
retained by the model in order
to be helpful at inference time.

1329
01:25:12,950 --> 01:25:19,190
So MMLU stands for
Massive Multitask Language

1330
01:25:19,190 --> 01:25:20,710
Understanding.

1331
01:25:20,710 --> 01:25:26,430
And this benchmark has
almost 60 different tasks

1332
01:25:26,430 --> 01:25:28,830
that are super diverse.

1333
01:25:28,830 --> 01:25:32,030
So it's not just one
specific topic is just

1334
01:25:32,030 --> 01:25:37,842
a bunch of topics, like
everyday life topics or very--

1335
01:25:37,842 --> 01:25:42,390
for example, there is law
or medicine, and everything

1336
01:25:42,390 --> 01:25:44,430
that you can think about.

1337
01:25:44,430 --> 01:25:48,870
And the benchmark is
redacted in a way that

1338
01:25:48,870 --> 01:25:54,070
can be easily measuring
an LLMs performance

1339
01:25:54,070 --> 01:25:57,390
and weighing that performance
with respect to others.

1340
01:25:57,390 --> 01:25:59,830
So it's not something
that is free-form.

1341
01:25:59,830 --> 01:26:05,190
It's something that
is very constrained.

1342
01:26:05,190 --> 01:26:09,530
There is a question, and then
you have four possible answers.

1343
01:26:09,530 --> 01:26:13,060
And you ask the LLM
to choose one of them.

1344
01:26:13,060 --> 01:26:17,490
So it's a bit like
CME 295 exams.

1345
01:26:17,490 --> 01:26:21,120
Part of the exam is also
multiple choice questions.

1346
01:26:21,120 --> 01:26:25,780
And it's a good way to
standardize the knowledge

1347
01:26:25,780 --> 01:26:26,740
evaluation.

1348
01:26:26,740 --> 01:26:28,360
And it's the same
that is used here.

1349
01:26:31,780 --> 01:26:36,100
And this is also a trend that
you see across benchmarks.

1350
01:26:36,100 --> 01:26:39,500
You don't ask the model to
just come up with some answer.

1351
01:26:39,500 --> 01:26:43,980
And you have maybe an
LLM-as-a-Judge just giving some

1352
01:26:43,980 --> 01:26:51,500
opinion about it because doing
so introduces another layer

1353
01:26:51,500 --> 01:26:53,280
of potential errors.

1354
01:26:53,280 --> 01:26:55,760
The LLM-as-a-Judge, as
I've seen mentioned,

1355
01:26:55,760 --> 01:26:57,280
isn't necessarily perfect.

1356
01:26:57,280 --> 01:27:04,180
So this framing enables us
to have a hard-coded way

1357
01:27:04,180 --> 01:27:07,040
to extract the answer
output by the LLM.

1358
01:27:07,040 --> 01:27:11,220
So typically, you would ask
it to output the right letter

1359
01:27:11,220 --> 01:27:13,660
at the end of each
question, which you can then

1360
01:27:13,660 --> 01:27:18,780
extract and then compare
with respect to the answer.

1361
01:27:18,780 --> 01:27:24,060
So giving some examples about
what is in this benchmark,

1362
01:27:24,060 --> 01:27:28,580
as I mentioned, you have all
sorts of fields in there.

1363
01:27:28,580 --> 01:27:33,420
And you will notice
that each problem mostly

1364
01:27:33,420 --> 01:27:36,860
requires some prior
knowledge about that topic.

1365
01:27:36,860 --> 01:27:41,440
So it's not purely logic
that will help you solve it.

1366
01:27:41,440 --> 01:27:44,620
And I think the last
example in this slide

1367
01:27:44,620 --> 01:27:47,740
is a good representation of
it, where you have something

1368
01:27:47,740 --> 01:27:52,500
in the domain of medicine, and
you have a bunch of numbers,

1369
01:27:52,500 --> 01:27:56,780
patient has this and
that, what would you

1370
01:27:56,780 --> 01:27:58,792
say-- where would you
say is the damage.

1371
01:27:58,792 --> 01:28:01,500
So it's typically something that
you could see in medicine books,

1372
01:28:01,500 --> 01:28:02,580
maybe.

1373
01:28:02,580 --> 01:28:06,370
And the same goes with other
fields, such as law, where

1374
01:28:06,370 --> 01:28:08,510
everything has been
codified somewhere,

1375
01:28:08,510 --> 01:28:11,330
and you need the knowledge
of that somewhere in order

1376
01:28:11,330 --> 01:28:14,650
to answer the question.

1377
01:28:14,650 --> 01:28:17,530
So this is the first kind.

1378
01:28:17,530 --> 01:28:21,370
And it's not the only
kind of benchmark.

1379
01:28:21,370 --> 01:28:23,670
So it's not the only
benchmark in this category.

1380
01:28:23,670 --> 01:28:27,110
You have other benchmarks that
can be in these categories,

1381
01:28:27,110 --> 01:28:29,370
but it's just one of them.

1382
01:28:29,370 --> 01:28:33,110
A second category
that you might see

1383
01:28:33,110 --> 01:28:36,890
are those that are in
the reasoning space.

1384
01:28:36,890 --> 01:28:40,890
So typically, these
are kinds of benchmarks

1385
01:28:40,890 --> 01:28:45,370
that require some
amount of thoughts

1386
01:28:45,370 --> 01:28:47,150
before outputting an answer.

1387
01:28:47,150 --> 01:28:49,410
So it assesses the
quality of the chain

1388
01:28:49,410 --> 01:28:53,210
of thoughts, or if you are
in the reasoning world,

1389
01:28:53,210 --> 01:28:57,750
maybe the quality of your think
tokens, but just more broadly,

1390
01:28:57,750 --> 01:29:04,290
your ability to infer a response
based on some reasoning.

1391
01:29:04,290 --> 01:29:10,290
And then for that, I'm going
to mention two examples, so one

1392
01:29:10,290 --> 01:29:12,450
in the field of
math and then one

1393
01:29:12,450 --> 01:29:16,730
other in the field of so-called
common sense reasoning that

1394
01:29:16,730 --> 01:29:23,050
is anchored in everyday
life, which is typically

1395
01:29:23,050 --> 01:29:27,250
the field that might be of
interest for your LLM users.

1396
01:29:27,250 --> 01:29:30,090
And we're going to
see that very soon.

1397
01:29:30,090 --> 01:29:35,010
So first, let's take a look at
the benchmark focused on math.

1398
01:29:35,010 --> 01:29:37,716
So how many of you about AIME?

1399
01:29:41,570 --> 01:29:47,770
So AIME is an exam that
high school students

1400
01:29:47,770 --> 01:29:54,210
sit for when they want to
participate to the Olympiads.

1401
01:29:54,210 --> 01:29:58,130
And typically, it's
a very hard test.

1402
01:29:58,130 --> 01:30:02,430
And it's covering math topics.

1403
01:30:02,430 --> 01:30:06,730
And then it's in a format that
is LLM-friendly because you

1404
01:30:06,730 --> 01:30:09,670
have a given problem statement.

1405
01:30:09,670 --> 01:30:14,650
And at the end, you ask the
student to write the response

1406
01:30:14,650 --> 01:30:19,130
into a three-digit number.

1407
01:30:19,130 --> 01:30:20,970
So it's very
well-constrained, which

1408
01:30:20,970 --> 01:30:25,650
makes it a right fit
to benchmark LLMs.

1409
01:30:25,650 --> 01:30:30,770
And just like the one
before, it's hard-coded.

1410
01:30:30,770 --> 01:30:37,730
And I give here some samples of
the AIME exam as seen this year.

1411
01:30:37,730 --> 01:30:38,440
So as you see--

1412
01:30:38,440 --> 01:30:40,350
I don't know if you
can read from afar,

1413
01:30:40,350 --> 01:30:42,530
but it's not super simple.

1414
01:30:42,530 --> 01:30:45,530
You have some one sentence.

1415
01:30:45,530 --> 01:30:47,650
So you think maybe it's
easy, but you actually

1416
01:30:47,650 --> 01:30:50,630
need to write down the reasoning
before finding the answer.

1417
01:30:50,630 --> 01:30:55,610
And this is what we want
to test the LLM for.

1418
01:30:55,610 --> 01:30:59,410
And then the second
kind of reasoning

1419
01:30:59,410 --> 01:31:02,280
that we mentioned here
was so-called common sense

1420
01:31:02,280 --> 01:31:03,400
reasoning.

1421
01:31:03,400 --> 01:31:06,480
And the one that is
often used these days

1422
01:31:06,480 --> 01:31:12,200
is PIQA, so Physical
Interaction, Question Answering.

1423
01:31:12,200 --> 01:31:16,280
So these are tasks that
are deeply grounded

1424
01:31:16,280 --> 01:31:19,620
into the physical real world.

1425
01:31:19,620 --> 01:31:22,520
So we have some samples at the
next slide that we'll show.

1426
01:31:22,520 --> 01:31:27,640
But it is still
reasoning-based questions,

1427
01:31:27,640 --> 01:31:30,120
but that will rely
on your understanding

1428
01:31:30,120 --> 01:31:32,360
on how things work
around you, not

1429
01:31:32,360 --> 01:31:37,680
necessarily math-based
but just everyday life.

1430
01:31:37,680 --> 01:31:42,800
And this time, it's not
multiple choice questions

1431
01:31:42,800 --> 01:31:46,320
over four answers,
like the MMLU.

1432
01:31:46,320 --> 01:31:49,280
It's over two only.

1433
01:31:49,280 --> 01:31:52,200
And you have the
20,000 examples.

1434
01:31:52,200 --> 01:31:55,440
And then here, a good
example that I really

1435
01:31:55,440 --> 01:31:59,800
liked from the samples
mentioned in the paper was,

1436
01:31:59,800 --> 01:32:02,800
how do I find something
I lost on the carpet?

1437
01:32:02,800 --> 01:32:07,960
So there is one solution that
says, vacuum with a solid seal.

1438
01:32:07,960 --> 01:32:12,800
And the other one is
vacuum with a hairnet.

1439
01:32:12,800 --> 01:32:15,500
And of course, when you
vacuum with the solid seal,

1440
01:32:15,500 --> 01:32:17,260
then the seal is,
of course, solid,

1441
01:32:17,260 --> 01:32:20,640
so no air can go through it.

1442
01:32:20,640 --> 01:32:24,620
But if you have a hairnet, you
will vacuum the whole thing.

1443
01:32:24,620 --> 01:32:28,280
And the thing that you lost
will be caught inside of it.

1444
01:32:28,280 --> 01:32:30,060
So what I mentioned
is common sense,

1445
01:32:30,060 --> 01:32:31,840
but it might not be obvious.

1446
01:32:31,840 --> 01:32:34,250
And this is what we tasked
the model to resolve.

1447
01:32:37,520 --> 01:32:41,920
So then one other major
area for benchmarks

1448
01:32:41,920 --> 01:32:49,000
is coding, where we want to
probe the model for solving

1449
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:51,640
complex questions, encoding.

1450
01:32:51,640 --> 01:32:56,430
And this has two main
uses in real life.

1451
01:32:56,430 --> 01:32:59,670
So one is aligned
with the use case

1452
01:32:59,670 --> 01:33:03,390
that I mentioned at the end of
last lecture, the one I liked

1453
01:33:03,390 --> 01:33:05,670
regarding AI assistant coding.

1454
01:33:05,670 --> 01:33:08,430
So these models,
they aim at being

1455
01:33:08,430 --> 01:33:10,430
used in that setting as well.

1456
01:33:10,430 --> 01:33:14,270
So you should make sure that
these benchmarks perform--

1457
01:33:14,270 --> 01:33:17,830
these benchmarks show that
these LLMs perform well in order

1458
01:33:17,830 --> 01:33:20,870
to be useful to your users.

1459
01:33:20,870 --> 01:33:24,950
And then a second reason
why benchmarking on coding

1460
01:33:24,950 --> 01:33:28,750
makes sense is that you have all
these tools that you might want

1461
01:33:28,750 --> 01:33:31,390
to use in an agentic setting.

1462
01:33:31,390 --> 01:33:35,590
And then these tools are written
maybe in a Python format.

1463
01:33:35,590 --> 01:33:40,830
So you want to ensure that your
model has the right ability

1464
01:33:40,830 --> 01:33:45,710
to read and write code so that
it can execute this tool calls

1465
01:33:45,710 --> 01:33:49,790
and then interpret what's
coming out of them.

1466
01:33:49,790 --> 01:33:53,574
So these are two, I
would say, motivations

1467
01:33:53,574 --> 01:34:00,350
that motivate us to find coding
useful here, even to the folks

1468
01:34:00,350 --> 01:34:02,210
that don't do coding at all.

1469
01:34:06,770 --> 01:34:12,390
And then one example of
such benchmark is SWE-bench.

1470
01:34:12,390 --> 01:34:15,310
So SWE-bench is--

1471
01:34:15,310 --> 01:34:18,230
I put a question mark here
because they didn't define

1472
01:34:18,230 --> 01:34:20,610
exactly what the acronym meant.

1473
01:34:20,610 --> 01:34:23,370
But it's likely that it meant
software engineering benchmarks.

1474
01:34:23,370 --> 01:34:27,630
So SWE is oftentimes the acronym
for software engineering.

1475
01:34:27,630 --> 01:34:32,150
And what they did is that
they looked at popular Python

1476
01:34:32,150 --> 01:34:35,390
repositories, and
they filtered down

1477
01:34:35,390 --> 01:34:39,550
those that contained
pull requests

1478
01:34:39,550 --> 01:34:44,550
that were solving an issue
and that introduced tests.

1479
01:34:44,550 --> 01:34:47,910
So you have some
before-after behavior

1480
01:34:47,910 --> 01:34:51,670
that you can quantitatively
assess with the tests that

1481
01:34:51,670 --> 01:34:53,150
are introduced.

1482
01:34:53,150 --> 01:34:57,030
And supposedly, if you
have pull request that

1483
01:34:57,030 --> 01:35:00,230
introduces some
tests and some fix,

1484
01:35:00,230 --> 01:35:04,150
you can fairly assume
that these tests were not

1485
01:35:04,150 --> 01:35:06,990
passing without the
fix, and that they

1486
01:35:06,990 --> 01:35:09,190
are passing after the fix.

1487
01:35:09,190 --> 01:35:12,910
So the fact that we
have these tests at-hand

1488
01:35:12,910 --> 01:35:18,030
is a good measure for us to
assess the quality of ethics.

1489
01:35:18,030 --> 01:35:21,250
So if you have heard of a
test-driven development,

1490
01:35:21,250 --> 01:35:25,170
it's all about having tests
and ensuring they pass.

1491
01:35:25,170 --> 01:35:27,410
And this is what it relies on.

1492
01:35:30,810 --> 01:35:36,410
And then here you ask these LLMs
to solve these GitHub issues.

1493
01:35:36,410 --> 01:35:40,950
And then you assess
whether they indeed

1494
01:35:40,950 --> 01:35:44,710
pass by looking
at the test status

1495
01:35:44,710 --> 01:35:50,120
before and after patching the
answer suggested by the LLM.

1496
01:35:52,920 --> 01:35:54,300
Great.

1497
01:35:54,300 --> 01:35:59,460
So here is a very nice figure
that the paper introducing

1498
01:35:59,460 --> 01:36:00,600
that benchmark gives.

1499
01:36:00,600 --> 01:36:03,900
So you're given a code base.

1500
01:36:03,900 --> 01:36:06,940
And then what you ask
the model for is a patch.

1501
01:36:06,940 --> 01:36:07,800
That is just it.

1502
01:36:07,800 --> 01:36:10,660
And then you patch
whatever the model has

1503
01:36:10,660 --> 01:36:13,260
provided to find the tests--

1504
01:36:13,260 --> 01:36:16,540
to find the test status.

1505
01:36:16,540 --> 01:36:19,060
And then one last
area that I want

1506
01:36:19,060 --> 01:36:25,100
to mention in the case of
base benchmarks is safety.

1507
01:36:25,100 --> 01:36:28,580
So when you see fancy
LLMs coming out,

1508
01:36:28,580 --> 01:36:33,780
you usually don't see in the
advertisements of modeling

1509
01:36:33,780 --> 01:36:40,150
benchmarks the safety part
because usually, safety

1510
01:36:40,150 --> 01:36:43,520
is a bit subjective with
respect to the LLM provider.

1511
01:36:43,520 --> 01:36:47,140
So every company
has its own policy.

1512
01:36:47,140 --> 01:36:51,180
So you cannot necessarily
compare a performance on a given

1513
01:36:51,180 --> 01:36:55,380
benchmark across models just
because all these providers

1514
01:36:55,380 --> 01:36:58,800
might not claim they want to
perfectly solve that benchmark

1515
01:36:58,800 --> 01:37:00,420
100%.

1516
01:37:00,420 --> 01:37:02,420
As a result, it's
not necessarily

1517
01:37:02,420 --> 01:37:05,820
a good measure of that field.

1518
01:37:05,820 --> 01:37:09,220
So if you look at model
cards, oftentimes, you

1519
01:37:09,220 --> 01:37:12,860
see a safety section being
mentioned in reports to say

1520
01:37:12,860 --> 01:37:14,580
the work that they have done.

1521
01:37:14,580 --> 01:37:18,140
But they don't necessarily
compare models with respect

1522
01:37:18,140 --> 01:37:19,480
to a given benchmark.

1523
01:37:22,180 --> 01:37:25,240
And usually, the
safety benchmarks,

1524
01:37:25,240 --> 01:37:28,660
they are fairly aligned
with what we think

1525
01:37:28,660 --> 01:37:30,600
should or should not happen.

1526
01:37:30,600 --> 01:37:33,660
But on top of it, you might
have additional policies

1527
01:37:33,660 --> 01:37:36,680
that maybe just policies.

1528
01:37:36,680 --> 01:37:40,560
So you have some human that
had to make some decision.

1529
01:37:40,560 --> 01:37:42,520
It might not be a
universal decision,

1530
01:37:42,520 --> 01:37:45,380
it's just a given decision.

1531
01:37:45,380 --> 01:37:52,460
So the benchmark's goal is to be
aligned with what kind of policy

1532
01:37:52,460 --> 01:37:57,820
the LLM provider has in mind in
order to be truly meaningful.

1533
01:37:57,820 --> 01:38:01,660
This is why when you
execute a safety benchmark,

1534
01:38:01,660 --> 01:38:04,380
you should check the
content of the benchmark

1535
01:38:04,380 --> 01:38:07,100
in order to put a
meaning behind it.

1536
01:38:07,100 --> 01:38:09,980
So here let's talk
about HarmBench,

1537
01:38:09,980 --> 01:38:15,340
which I am supposing it means
harmful behavior benchmark.

1538
01:38:15,340 --> 01:38:18,980
So this benchmark
has four categories,

1539
01:38:18,980 --> 01:38:26,500
the so-called standard category
that is categorizing quote,

1540
01:38:26,500 --> 01:38:30,180
unquote, "vanilla"
harmful behavior.

1541
01:38:30,180 --> 01:38:33,300
Then you have
copyright category that

1542
01:38:33,300 --> 01:38:37,700
is assessing the model's
ability to generate copyrighted

1543
01:38:37,700 --> 01:38:40,260
content, which we do not want.

1544
01:38:40,260 --> 01:38:45,410
And then the two last ones,
contextual and multimodal,

1545
01:38:45,410 --> 01:38:50,110
both of them are contextual
based on a given modality.

1546
01:38:50,110 --> 01:38:53,590
So contextual is on
the text modality.

1547
01:38:53,590 --> 01:38:59,170
And then multimodal is with
other modalities than text.

1548
01:38:59,170 --> 01:39:02,610
So we're going to see an
example at the next slide.

1549
01:39:02,610 --> 01:39:06,890
And here you don't
have the same ability

1550
01:39:06,890 --> 01:39:09,850
to assess performance
on this benchmark based

1551
01:39:09,850 --> 01:39:14,490
on some hard-coded match because
these harmful statements might

1552
01:39:14,490 --> 01:39:16,210
be open-ended.

1553
01:39:16,210 --> 01:39:20,170
And you cannot possibly just
solve all of these by RegEx

1554
01:39:20,170 --> 01:39:21,530
matching.

1555
01:39:21,530 --> 01:39:26,010
For example, one example
in the standard category

1556
01:39:26,010 --> 01:39:34,130
of this benchmark tries
to entice harmful behavior

1557
01:39:34,130 --> 01:39:37,050
into executing something
that is harmful.

1558
01:39:37,050 --> 01:39:41,610
And the paper mentions--

1559
01:39:41,610 --> 01:39:43,870
distinguishes something
that is very interesting.

1560
01:39:43,870 --> 01:39:48,490
So it distinguishes
model quality with safety

1561
01:39:48,490 --> 01:39:51,570
by saying that if
the model tries

1562
01:39:51,570 --> 01:39:55,090
to do the harmful behavior,
even if it wasn't successful,

1563
01:39:55,090 --> 01:39:59,170
because it was not of a
good quality enough, then

1564
01:39:59,170 --> 01:40:03,530
it's enough to count the
attack as successful.

1565
01:40:03,530 --> 01:40:06,570
And for that, they
trained some classifier

1566
01:40:06,570 --> 01:40:09,630
to recognize these cases.

1567
01:40:09,630 --> 01:40:12,890
This is the only
benchmark among those

1568
01:40:12,890 --> 01:40:16,250
that I presented here that is
done based on a classifier that

1569
01:40:16,250 --> 01:40:19,970
can itself be prone
to error compared

1570
01:40:19,970 --> 01:40:28,090
to others that are very grounded
in constrained set of values.

1571
01:40:28,090 --> 01:40:30,890
And as promised, here
is a few examples as

1572
01:40:30,890 --> 01:40:32,030
mentioned in the paper.

1573
01:40:32,030 --> 01:40:36,850
So here we test whether
you can unlock a door

1574
01:40:36,850 --> 01:40:38,150
that you shouldn't unlock.

1575
01:40:38,150 --> 01:40:44,760
And then here the test is on
influencing someone with respect

1576
01:40:44,760 --> 01:40:46,546
to some election.

1577
01:40:46,546 --> 01:40:48,506
These are not safe behaviors.

1578
01:40:52,200 --> 01:40:52,700
Great.

1579
01:40:52,700 --> 01:40:55,760
So I mentioned everything
so far that you

1580
01:40:55,760 --> 01:40:58,840
could solve without tools.

1581
01:40:58,840 --> 01:41:00,560
So of course, I say, you could.

1582
01:41:00,560 --> 01:41:03,100
Some of them, you could use
tools, of course, to solve them.

1583
01:41:03,100 --> 01:41:08,400
But what about measuring
the behavior of agents?

1584
01:41:08,400 --> 01:41:11,240
So for here, you have
an interesting benchmark

1585
01:41:11,240 --> 01:41:16,080
called tau-bench, where
tau is a Greek letter

1586
01:41:16,080 --> 01:41:21,220
that actually, you can write
it as tool agent users.

1587
01:41:21,220 --> 01:41:23,720
And this is why we say tau.

1588
01:41:23,720 --> 01:41:27,640
And it's a benchmark
that provides

1589
01:41:27,640 --> 01:41:30,920
across two different
fields, so the airline

1590
01:41:30,920 --> 01:41:34,920
and the retail field,
a set of tools.

1591
01:41:34,920 --> 01:41:40,120
And it gives a set of policies,
things that the agent can

1592
01:41:40,120 --> 01:41:41,840
and cannot do.

1593
01:41:41,840 --> 01:41:45,720
And then what you do is that
you have a set of tasks.

1594
01:41:45,720 --> 01:41:53,040
So tasks are problem statements
that you give a given user.

1595
01:41:53,040 --> 01:41:55,920
And the goal is for
the user to achieve

1596
01:41:55,920 --> 01:41:59,000
that task through the agent.

1597
01:41:59,000 --> 01:42:01,280
And the interesting
thing about tau-bench

1598
01:42:01,280 --> 01:42:05,300
is that tau-bench is
language model-simulated.

1599
01:42:05,300 --> 01:42:09,300
So the user interaction with
the agent, as you can imagine,

1600
01:42:09,300 --> 01:42:14,640
cannot be hard-coded because
further terms will depend

1601
01:42:14,640 --> 01:42:16,140
on previous ones.

1602
01:42:16,140 --> 01:42:19,960
So let's say, you say something
as a user and your agent

1603
01:42:19,960 --> 01:42:22,680
decides to do
something, then you

1604
01:42:22,680 --> 01:42:26,720
need the context of what it
has done in order to continue

1605
01:42:26,720 --> 01:42:27,780
the conversation.

1606
01:42:27,780 --> 01:42:30,000
And this is why you
have this simulation

1607
01:42:30,000 --> 01:42:33,600
aspect that the paper
introduces that is typically

1608
01:42:33,600 --> 01:42:41,680
done by a separate big model
that plays the role of the user.

1609
01:42:41,680 --> 01:42:47,300
And here we have an example of
the task of changing a flight.

1610
01:42:47,300 --> 01:42:48,580
So you have given tools.

1611
01:42:48,580 --> 01:42:55,360
The agent tries to help the
user to achieve that goal.

1612
01:42:55,360 --> 01:42:59,120
And at the end of it,
we assess whether it's

1613
01:42:59,120 --> 01:43:01,800
successful in doing
so by calculating

1614
01:43:01,800 --> 01:43:05,540
a reward that's a function
of the database change.

1615
01:43:05,540 --> 01:43:08,820
So let's say, the user
has changed their tickets,

1616
01:43:08,820 --> 01:43:12,560
so we want to see if
the database has indeed

1617
01:43:12,560 --> 01:43:17,580
the state that we're looking
for and/or a given action.

1618
01:43:17,580 --> 01:43:20,480
So maybe the action
of canceling is one

1619
01:43:20,480 --> 01:43:23,280
that is the goal of this task.

1620
01:43:23,280 --> 01:43:26,320
So this is part of the reward.

1621
01:43:26,320 --> 01:43:31,520
And the paper that introduces
this benchmark talks

1622
01:43:31,520 --> 01:43:36,710
about a concept that
is a funny word play.

1623
01:43:36,710 --> 01:43:39,630
With respect to
the metric that we

1624
01:43:39,630 --> 01:43:42,390
had talked about at
the last lecture,

1625
01:43:42,390 --> 01:43:46,056
we had introduced pass@k.

1626
01:43:46,056 --> 01:43:51,590
And then this paper
talks about pass hat k,

1627
01:43:51,590 --> 01:43:58,350
which is the probability
that all k attempts succeed.

1628
01:43:58,350 --> 01:44:02,790
And then why is that
relevant metric here?

1629
01:44:02,790 --> 01:44:06,990
So as you have seen, the
airline and retail domains

1630
01:44:06,990 --> 01:44:09,710
were ones that were chosen here.

1631
01:44:09,710 --> 01:44:12,110
And then an agent
in the loop here

1632
01:44:12,110 --> 01:44:18,470
could be a way to see
if automating the agent

1633
01:44:18,470 --> 01:44:21,030
side of things could help.

1634
01:44:21,030 --> 01:44:24,590
And in order to truly
know whether it can help,

1635
01:44:24,590 --> 01:44:28,290
you want to have reliability
and consistency in mind.

1636
01:44:28,290 --> 01:44:31,710
So if you execute
the task k times,

1637
01:44:31,710 --> 01:44:37,630
you don't want pass@k, the
probability that at least one

1638
01:44:37,630 --> 01:44:38,650
of them succeeds.

1639
01:44:38,650 --> 01:44:41,790
You want the probability
that all of them succeeds,

1640
01:44:41,790 --> 01:44:44,750
which is why this
metric matters.

1641
01:44:44,750 --> 01:44:49,350
So if we had more time, I
would have derived the formula

1642
01:44:49,350 --> 01:44:57,070
to find pass hat k with
respect to the parameters

1643
01:44:57,070 --> 01:44:58,130
of the problem.

1644
01:44:58,130 --> 01:45:00,070
But I will refer you
to the derivation

1645
01:45:00,070 --> 01:45:03,770
that Afshine has done last time.

1646
01:45:03,770 --> 01:45:07,493
I just want you to be convinced
that this is indeed the formula.

1647
01:45:07,493 --> 01:45:08,910
So if you're not
convinced, please

1648
01:45:08,910 --> 01:45:12,830
feel free to do it at home.

1649
01:45:12,830 --> 01:45:17,830
And moving on, we talked
about all these benchmarks.

1650
01:45:17,830 --> 01:45:21,310
Now let's see how they
are grounded in reality.

1651
01:45:21,310 --> 01:45:24,070
So by now, I think
everyone of you

1652
01:45:24,070 --> 01:45:28,270
has seen the new Gemini
launch a few days ago.

1653
01:45:28,270 --> 01:45:31,950
So this was the
report that was sent

1654
01:45:31,950 --> 01:45:36,910
to everyone to justify that the
performance here was better.

1655
01:45:36,910 --> 01:45:40,230
And you can see that
what we introduced here

1656
01:45:40,230 --> 01:45:43,150
is mentioned in some format.

1657
01:45:43,150 --> 01:45:48,490
So the reasoning part on
AIME and PIQA is there.

1658
01:45:48,490 --> 01:45:50,510
And you will see that
some of these benchmarks

1659
01:45:50,510 --> 01:45:59,270
are derived in a flavor that
introduces multilinguality--

1660
01:45:59,270 --> 01:46:01,710
multi-languages.

1661
01:46:01,710 --> 01:46:03,150
So this is the case for PIQA.

1662
01:46:03,150 --> 01:46:05,750
Instead of PIQA,
it's global PIQA.

1663
01:46:05,750 --> 01:46:09,590
And then for coding, it
uses a flavor of SWE-bench.

1664
01:46:09,590 --> 01:46:14,050
And tool use, it uses also
a flavor of tau-bench,

1665
01:46:14,050 --> 01:46:15,740
which is tau squared bench.

1666
01:46:19,310 --> 01:46:22,790
And a few last
words, here I just

1667
01:46:22,790 --> 01:46:26,350
want to say that benchmarks
are here to characterize

1668
01:46:26,350 --> 01:46:29,250
the profile of your LLM.

1669
01:46:29,250 --> 01:46:33,460
So it's not all good or all bad.

1670
01:46:33,460 --> 01:46:37,140
Maybe some of your LLMs
will have some strength

1671
01:46:37,140 --> 01:46:39,220
and some weaknesses.

1672
01:46:39,220 --> 01:46:43,260
And your personal
experience might

1673
01:46:43,260 --> 01:46:45,860
guide you to use one
specific one with respect

1674
01:46:45,860 --> 01:46:47,600
to others in given situations.

1675
01:46:47,600 --> 01:46:50,832
So if I had to just give
my personal experience,

1676
01:46:50,832 --> 01:46:56,100
I know that the Sonnet models
are very helpful for coding.

1677
01:46:56,100 --> 01:47:00,060
And whenever I want outputs
that are fast and cheap,

1678
01:47:00,060 --> 01:47:02,340
Gemini Flash is usually good.

1679
01:47:02,340 --> 01:47:06,390
But these are not, by any
means, global recommendations.

1680
01:47:06,390 --> 01:47:08,340
Your own use case and
your own experience

1681
01:47:08,340 --> 01:47:12,420
can guide you into having
a profile of models that

1682
01:47:12,420 --> 01:47:15,620
suits your tasks best.

1683
01:47:15,620 --> 01:47:22,140
And you can interestingly plot
the performance of your models

1684
01:47:22,140 --> 01:47:24,380
with respect to
the other dimension

1685
01:47:24,380 --> 01:47:27,820
that you care about, which
is price, for example,

1686
01:47:27,820 --> 01:47:32,900
and see for a given price, what
is the best model you can use.

1687
01:47:32,900 --> 01:47:36,420
And then the border
that you see on the best

1688
01:47:36,420 --> 01:47:41,340
models for that specific metric
is called the Pareto frontier.

1689
01:47:41,340 --> 01:47:43,820
And you might have a Pareto
frontier with respect

1690
01:47:43,820 --> 01:47:49,900
to several aspects, so cost,
safety, context length.

1691
01:47:49,900 --> 01:47:53,780
And then a few words
regarding data contamination,

1692
01:47:53,780 --> 01:47:55,500
one thing about
these benchmarks is

1693
01:47:55,500 --> 01:47:59,740
that they are as good as the
assumption of whether you

1694
01:47:59,740 --> 01:48:03,100
have seen the actual
benchmark results or not.

1695
01:48:03,100 --> 01:48:04,800
So make sure you
haven't seen them.

1696
01:48:04,800 --> 01:48:08,580
And for that, people
introduce hash values.

1697
01:48:08,580 --> 01:48:11,380
In the case of tool use, they
introduce a blocklist in order

1698
01:48:11,380 --> 01:48:16,540
to not access websites that
might contain the responses,

1699
01:48:16,540 --> 01:48:20,060
or in the case of math,
we have the luxury

1700
01:48:20,060 --> 01:48:26,890
of evaluating on new tests that
the model has for sure not seen.

1701
01:48:26,890 --> 01:48:32,250
And Goodhart's law
is a very good adage

1702
01:48:32,250 --> 01:48:36,310
that says, when a
measure becomes a target,

1703
01:48:36,310 --> 01:48:38,690
it ceases to be a good measure.

1704
01:48:38,690 --> 01:48:41,450
So all these
benchmark results are

1705
01:48:41,450 --> 01:48:45,530
to be weighed against what
you're truly looking for.

1706
01:48:45,530 --> 01:48:48,050
And then these benchmark
results don't necessarily

1707
01:48:48,050 --> 01:48:51,100
tell you whether a model
is good for you or not.

1708
01:48:53,890 --> 01:48:57,170
We had talked
about ChatBotArena.

1709
01:48:57,170 --> 01:48:58,690
In one of the
previous lectures, it

1710
01:48:58,690 --> 01:49:04,170
can be one way to balance the
real-life performance of these.

1711
01:49:04,170 --> 01:49:08,250
But I would say, ultimately,
should be the one trying out

1712
01:49:08,250 --> 01:49:10,690
these best models and
see for yourself which

1713
01:49:10,690 --> 01:49:14,090
one corresponds to your best.

1714
01:49:14,090 --> 01:49:16,890
And with that, I hope you all
have a great Thanksgiving.

1715
